msgid "A clean, uncluttered background is ideal. A plain wall, bookshelf, or tidy home office space all work well. Avoid virtual backgrounds if possible, as they can create distracting visual artifacts, especially with movement. If your physical space is not suitable, a subtle, professional virtual background is better than a messy room. Ensure there is nothing embarrassing or distracting visible in the frame."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/networking-linkedin.ts
msgid ""
"A cohesive professional online presence requires consistency across every platform where you are visible. Your name, photo, headline, and professional narrative should align across LinkedIn, your personal website, Twitter, GitHub, and any other professional profiles. When a recruiter encounters you on LinkedIn and then visits your personal website, the experience should feel seamless rather than disjointed.\n"
"\n"
"Create a professional bio in three lengths: a one-sentence version for social media profiles, a one-paragraph version for speaker bios and guest post bylines, and a full-page version for your personal website's About page. Having these prepared in advance makes it easy to maintain consistency as you create or update profiles across different platforms. Include the same core keywords and professional identity markers in all three versions.\n"
"\n"
"Cross-link your profiles to create a connected web of your professional presence. Your LinkedIn should link to your personal website. Your personal website should link to LinkedIn, GitHub, and relevant social profiles. Your email signature should include links to your most important profiles. This interconnected structure makes it easy for anyone who discovers you on one platform to explore your complete professional presence, and it signals to search engines that all of these profiles belong to the same person, strengthening your overall search ranking.\n"
"\n"
"Your email signature is an often-overlooked component of your online presence. Every email you send is a branding opportunity. Include your full name, professional title, phone number, and links to your LinkedIn profile and personal website. For professionals who create content, adding a link to your latest article or publication in your email signature drives traffic and demonstrates ongoing thought leadership with zero additional effort.\n"
"\n"
"Consistency extends to the tone and style of your communications across platforms. If your LinkedIn profile positions you as a thoughtful, analytical professional, your Twitter posts should not be exclusively casual or off-topic. This does not mean every platform needs identical content, but the overall impression should be coherent. A recruiter who encounters you on three different platforms should walk away with a consistent understanding of your professional identity, values, and expertise."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-formats.ts
msgid "A combination resume can be kept to one to two pages if you are strategic about content. The key is to avoid redundancy between your skills section and work experience section. Be concise with each bullet point, focusing on high-impact achievements. For most professionals, a well-organized combination resume fits comfortably on two pages, which is perfectly acceptable for candidates with five or more years of experience."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-formats.ts
msgid ""
"A combination resume, also known as a hybrid resume, merges the best elements of the chronological and functional formats into a single, versatile document. It begins with a prominent skills or qualifications section that highlights your core competencies, followed by a chronological listing of your work experience. This dual structure allows you to lead with what you can do while also providing the timeline and context that recruiters expect.\n"
"\n"
"The combination format was developed in response to the limitations of both the chronological and functional formats. The chronological resume is excellent for candidates with steady career progressions but can work against those with gaps or career changes. The functional resume addresses those challenges but often raises suspicion among recruiters and performs poorly with applicant tracking systems. The combination format bridges this gap by offering a middle ground that serves a wider range of job seekers.\n"
"\n"
"In practice, a combination resume typically includes the following sections: contact information, professional summary, core skills or competencies organized by category, work experience in reverse chronological order, education, and optional sections such as certifications or volunteer work. The skills section usually appears immediately after the professional summary and before the work experience, positioning your strongest qualifications where they will be seen first.\n"
"\n"
"The key distinction between a combination resume and a chronological resume with a skills section is emphasis and depth. In a combination resume, the skills section is not merely a list of keywords. It includes specific accomplishments and evidence that demonstrate each competency. Meanwhile, the work experience section may be slightly condensed compared to a pure chronological resume, with fewer bullet points per role since many of your achievements are already detailed in the skills section above."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/job-search-strategies.ts
msgid ""
"A company's financial health directly impacts your job security, compensation growth, and career trajectory. For publicly traded companies, annual reports, quarterly earnings calls, and SEC filings provide detailed financial information. Key metrics to evaluate include revenue growth rate, profitability, debt levels, cash reserves, and forward guidance from leadership.\n"
"\n"
"For private companies, financial information is harder to obtain but not impossible. Crunchbase and PitchBook track funding rounds, valuations, and investors for venture-backed companies. A company that recently raised a large funding round at an increasing valuation is likely in a strong growth phase. Conversely, a company that has not raised new funding in several years or has taken on significant debt may face challenges.\n"
"\n"
"Industry context matters when evaluating financials. A company losing money while growing revenue at 100 percent annually in a land-grab market is in a fundamentally different position than a mature company with declining revenue and mounting losses. Understanding the company's business model, competitive landscape, and growth stage helps you interpret financial data accurately.\n"
"\n"
"News coverage from business publications like Bloomberg, TechCrunch, Fortune, and industry-specific outlets provides context on the company's strategic direction, competitive position, and market perception. Look for patterns in coverage over the past 12 to 24 months. Consistent positive coverage about growth, innovation, and market leadership is a good sign. Coverage focused on layoffs, executive turnover, or competitive pressure warrants caution.\n"
"\n"
"If the company is a startup, evaluate the strength of its investors and board. Top-tier venture capital firms and experienced board members provide not only capital but strategic guidance, industry connections, and operational support that increase the probability of success. The identity of who is betting on the company tells you a lot about its prospects."
msgstr ""

