#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-fundamentals.ts
msgid ""
"A well-crafted skills section serves multiple purposes: it provides a quick snapshot of your capabilities for human readers and serves as a keyword-rich section that helps your resume pass through ATS filters. This section should be strategically curated rather than an exhaustive list of every skill you have ever acquired.\n"
"\n"
"Divide your skills into categories when possible, such as \"Technical Skills,\" \"Software Proficiency,\" \"Languages,\" and \"Certifications.\" This organization makes the section easier to scan and helps recruiters quickly identify the competencies they are looking for. A software developer might categorize skills into \"Programming Languages,\" \"Frameworks & Libraries,\" \"Cloud Platforms,\" and \"Tools & Methodologies.\"\n"
"\n"
"Prioritize hard skills over soft skills in this section. Hard skills are specific, teachable abilities that can be measured, such as programming languages, data analysis tools, design software, or foreign languages. Soft skills like \"communication,\" \"leadership,\" and \"problem-solving\" are better demonstrated through your work experience bullet points rather than simply listed. If a recruiter sees \"excellent communication skills\" listed alongside \"Python\" and \"SQL,\" the soft skill claim carries no evidence while the hard skills are verifiable.\n"
"\n"
"Mirror the language of the job description when listing your skills. If the posting asks for \"proficiency in Adobe Creative Suite,\" use that exact phrase rather than listing individual applications separately. If it mentions \"agile methodology,\" do not write \"scrum\" unless the posting specifically uses that term. ATS software often matches keywords exactly, and using synonyms or alternative phrasings can cause your resume to score lower even if you possess the required skills.\n"
"\n"
"Be honest about your proficiency levels. Claiming expert-level skill in a tool you have only used a few times can backfire spectacularly in a technical interview. Many job seekers use a simple categorization system such as \"Proficient,\" \"Intermediate,\" and \"Familiar\" to indicate their comfort level with each skill. Others choose not to indicate proficiency levels at all, which is also acceptable. Whatever approach you take, be prepared to discuss and demonstrate any skill listed on your resume."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/job-search-strategies.ts
msgid ""
"A well-designed spreadsheet is the simplest and most flexible tracking tool available. Create columns for: company name, position title, job posting URL, date applied, application method (direct site, LinkedIn, referral, recruiter), contact person, email or phone, current status (applied, phone screen scheduled, interview scheduled, offer, rejected, no response), follow-up date, and notes.\n"
"\n"
"Add conditional formatting to make your tracker visually scannable at a glance. Color-code the status column so applied is yellow, interviews are green, rejections are red, and offers are blue. Add highlighting for follow-up dates that are today or overdue. These visual cues ensure you never miss an action item when reviewing your tracker.\n"
"\n"
"Include a separate tab for networking contacts that tracks the person's name, company, how you connected, date of last contact, what you discussed, and planned next steps. Many of your best leads will come through networking rather than direct applications, and tracking these relationships with the same rigor as job applications ensures you follow up appropriately and maintain the relationships that generate opportunities.\n"
"\n"
"Create a third tab for interview preparation that logs interview dates, interviewers, questions asked, your responses, and post-interview reflections. This interview journal helps you identify patterns in the questions you receive, improve your responses over time, and remember details that are relevant for follow-up communications and subsequent interview rounds.\n"
"\n"
"Review your tracker at the start and end of each search day. The morning review tells you what follow-ups are due and which applications need attention. The evening review ensures all of the day's activities are logged and tomorrow's priorities are clear. This five-minute habit at each end of the day prevents the information gaps that derail an organized search."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"A well-structured cover letter follows a clear, logical flow that guides the reader from your introduction through your qualifications and into a compelling call to action. The standard cover letter structure consists of four key components: the header, opening paragraph, body paragraphs, and closing paragraph. Each serves a distinct purpose and should be crafted with intention.\n"
"\n"
"Your header should include your full name, contact information, the date, and the recipient's details. Keep this professional and consistent with the formatting of your resume to create a cohesive application package. Many applicants use a matching header design across both documents, which creates a polished, branded appearance.\n"
"\n"
"The opening paragraph is your hook -- it should immediately capture attention and establish why you are writing. The body paragraphs (typically one or two) are where you present your strongest qualifications, tell relevant stories, and draw direct connections between your experience and the job requirements. The closing paragraph should reiterate your enthusiasm, include a clear call to action, and thank the reader for their consideration.\n"
"\n"
"Throughout the letter, maintain a professional but personable tone. Write in the first person and use active voice to convey confidence and energy. Avoid passive constructions like \"the project was managed by me\" in favor of direct statements like \"I managed a cross-functional project that delivered a 30% increase in operational efficiency.\" Every sentence should serve a purpose -- if it does not add value, remove it.\n"
"\n"
"Aim for a length of three to four paragraphs, fitting comfortably on a single page. Most hiring managers spend less than a minute reviewing a cover letter, so every word needs to earn its place. White space and clear paragraph breaks improve readability and make your key points easier to scan."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/interview-preparation.ts
msgid "A well-structured STAR response should take between one and two minutes to deliver. Spend roughly fifteen percent on the Situation, fifteen percent on the Task, fifty percent on the Action, and twenty percent on the Result. If the interviewer wants more detail, they will ask follow-up questions. Keeping your initial response concise shows respect for their time and strong communication skills."
msgstr ""

#: src/routes/dashboard/tools/-components/thank-you-components.tsx
msgid "A well-written thank you letter can make the difference between two equally qualified candidates. It demonstrates your professionalism, motivation, and ability to communicate effectively. Remember to personalize each letter based on the specific interview."
msgstr ""

