#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-fundamentals.ts
msgid "Academic CVs and Length"
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-fundamentals.ts
msgid ""
"Academic CVs operate under entirely different length expectations than industry resumes. In academia, a CV is a comprehensive record of your entire scholarly career, and there is no maximum page limit. An early-career academic may have a two-to-four-page CV, while a tenured professor with decades of publications, presentations, grants, and committee service may have a CV that extends to 20 pages or more.\n"
"\n"
"The content of an academic CV includes sections that would never appear on an industry resume: publications (books, journal articles, conference papers, and working papers), presentations, teaching experience, courses taught, research grants and fellowships, academic honors and awards, professional service (committee memberships, journal reviewing, editorial board positions), and dissertation or thesis details. Each of these sections may grow substantially over the course of an academic career.\n"
"\n"
"When listing publications, use the citation style standard in your discipline (APA, MLA, Chicago, etc.) and include all co-authors. Publications are typically divided into categories: peer-reviewed journal articles, book chapters, conference proceedings, working papers, and other publications. Many academics also include works under review or in preparation to indicate their active research agenda.\n"
"\n"
"If you are an academic transitioning to industry, you will need to convert your CV into a resume format. This means cutting the document from many pages to one or two, removing academic-specific sections, and reframing your research and teaching experience in terms of business-relevant skills. Emphasize project management (grants), team leadership (research groups), communication (publications and presentations), and analytical skills (research methodology) rather than listing every paper you have published."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/industry-guides.ts
msgid ""
"Academic projects are among the most underutilized assets on entry-level resumes. Many graduates dismiss their coursework as merely academic, failing to recognize that complex projects, research papers, and capstone assignments often involve the same skills and processes used in professional settings. A marketing student who developed a comprehensive campaign strategy for a real client through a university partnership has legitimate marketing experience. A computer science student who built a full-stack application as a senior project has genuine software development experience.\n"
"\n"
"When listing academic projects, treat them with the same professional formatting you would use for work experience. Include the project title, the course or program context, the timeframe, and your specific contributions and outcomes. Use action verbs and quantify results where possible. If your project was selected for presentation at a conference, adopted by the client partner, or recognized with an award, these outcomes carry significant weight and should be highlighted prominently.\n"
"\n"
"Internships, even short or unpaid ones, deserve prominent placement on an entry-level resume. They demonstrate that a professional organization trusted you enough to bring you into their operation, and they provide the most directly relevant experience you may have. Format internship entries like full employment entries, with the company name, your title, dates, and achievement-oriented bullet points. If your internship involved meaningful project work, describe the project scope, your role, and the outcome rather than simply listing daily tasks.\n"
"\n"
"Volunteer work and extracurricular activities fill the gap for candidates who did not complete internships. Leadership roles in student organizations, consistent volunteer commitments, athletic team participation, and community involvement all provide evidence of reliability, initiative, and interpersonal skills. The key is framing these activities in professional terms. Do not write that you helped out at a food bank. Instead, write that you coordinated weekly food distribution for two hundred families, managed a team of fifteen volunteers, and streamlined inventory tracking to reduce food waste by twenty percent."
msgstr ""

