#: src/routes/dashboard/tools/ats-checker.tsx
msgid "Applicant Tracking Systems (ATS) filter out 75% of resumes before a human ever sees them. Check your resume against industry standards to ensure it passes through."
msgstr "Les systèmes de suivi des candidatures (ATS) éliminent 75 % des CV avant qu'un humain ne les voie. Vérifiez votre CV par rapport aux standards du secteur pour vous assurer qu'il passe le filtre."

#: src/data/wiki/categories/industry-guides.ts
msgid ""
"Applicant tracking systems are the first gate your engineering resume must pass through, and technical roles often have the most aggressive keyword filtering. Understanding how ATS parsing works and optimizing your resume accordingly is not about gaming the system; it is about ensuring your genuine qualifications are recognized by the automated tools that employers rely on.\n"
"\n"
"Start by analyzing the job description for explicit technology requirements, required years of experience, and key phrases that describe the role's core responsibilities. Mirror these terms exactly in your resume where they honestly apply. If the job description asks for experience with PostgreSQL, do not only list SQL or relational databases; include PostgreSQL by name. If the posting mentions continuous integration and continuous deployment, use both the full phrase and the CI/CD abbreviation to cover both keyword matching approaches.\n"
"\n"
"Resume format matters significantly for ATS parsing. Use a clean, single-column layout with standard section headers such as Experience, Education, Skills, and Projects. Avoid tables, columns, text boxes, headers and footers, and embedded images, as these elements frequently cause parsing failures that result in garbled or missing information. Save your resume in PDF format unless the application specifically requests a different format, as modern ATS platforms handle PDFs reliably.\n"
"\n"
"For engineering roles at technology companies, be aware that many organizations use specialized technical screening tools in addition to standard ATS platforms. These tools may analyze your GitHub profile, parse your LinkedIn for technology keywords, or even evaluate the structure and content of your resume against role-specific models. Ensure consistency across all your professional profiles, and include links to your GitHub, portfolio, or personal site if they showcase relevant work.\n"
"\n"
"Finally, tailor each version of your resume to the specific role family you are targeting. A resume optimized for backend engineering positions should emphasize different skills and projects than one targeting DevOps or data engineering roles, even if your experience spans multiple domains. Maintaining two to three base versions of your resume and customizing them for each application is significantly more effective than sending a single generic document to every opportunity."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-sections.ts
msgid ""
"Applicant tracking systems scan your resume for keyword matches before a human ever sees it. Your summary is prime real estate for embedding critical keywords because it sits at the top of the document. Review the job description and identify the three to five most important terms, then weave them naturally into your summary.\n"
"\n"
"For example, if a job posting emphasizes \"project management,\" \"Agile methodology,\" and \"stakeholder communication,\" your summary should include those exact phrases. But do not keyword-stuff: the text still needs to read naturally to the human recruiter who reviews it after the ATS pass.\n"
"\n"
"Use the same job title that appears in the posting. If the posting says \"Software Development Engineer\" and your previous title was \"Software Engineer II,\" consider using the posting's exact phrasing in your summary while listing your actual title in the experience section.\n"
"\n"
"Mirror the tone and language of the company. A startup that writes casual, energetic job postings will respond differently than a Fortune 500 firm with formal language. Matching tone signals cultural alignment without explicitly stating it.\n"
"\n"
"One effective technique is to read the posting aloud and note which words repeat. Repeated terms indicate priority requirements. Ensure those terms appear in your summary, ideally within the first two sentences where both ATS parsers and human eyes focus most attention."
msgstr ""

