#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"Choosing the right font for your cover letter might seem like a minor detail, but typography significantly affects readability and the overall impression your letter creates. The best cover letter fonts are professional, easy to read on both screens and print, and consistent with the font used on your resume.\n"
"\n"
"Stick to widely available, professional serif or sans-serif fonts. Excellent choices include Calibri, Cambria, Garamond, Georgia, Helvetica, and Arial. These fonts are universally installed on virtually all computers and render consistently across platforms. Avoid decorative, script, or novelty fonts that can appear unprofessional or become illegible at smaller sizes.\n"
"\n"
"Set your font size between 10.5 and 12 points for body text. This range provides optimal readability without forcing you to shrink text to fit more content on the page. If you find yourself reducing the font size below 10.5 to fit everything, your letter is too long and needs editing. Your name in the header can be slightly larger (14 to 16 points) to create visual hierarchy.\n"
"\n"
"Line spacing should be set to 1.0 or 1.15 for body text, with a full blank line between paragraphs. This spacing creates enough white space to prevent the letter from feeling dense while keeping it compact enough to fit on one page. Margins should be set between 0.75 and 1 inch on all sides, with 1 inch being the most common and safest choice.\n"
"\n"
"Consistency is the most important typography rule. Use the same font family, size, and style throughout your cover letter, and match these choices to your resume. If your resume uses Calibri at 11 points, your cover letter should use Calibri at 11 points. This attention to visual consistency signals meticulousness and professionalism."
msgstr ""

