#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-sections.ts
msgid ""
"Despite the general preference for summaries, there are specific situations where a resume objective, or a modern hybrid version, makes strategic sense.\n"
"\n"
"Career changers benefit from objectives because they need to explicitly state their target direction. When your work history does not obviously align with the role you are pursuing, an objective provides the context that prevents the recruiter from dismissing your resume as irrelevant. For example: \"Former financial analyst transitioning into UX design, bringing five years of data-driven decision-making to create intuitive, user-centered digital experiences.\"\n"
"\n"
"New graduates with minimal work experience often lack the material needed for a compelling summary. In this case, a goal-oriented statement that connects their education and aspirations to the target role can be effective: \"Computer science graduate from Al Akhawayn University with strong foundations in algorithm design and a passion for back-end development, seeking an entry-level software engineering role to contribute to scalable systems.\"\n"
"\n"
"Candidates applying for positions in a specific geographic area or industry can use an objective to signal their intent. If relocation or industry focus is a key factor in the hiring decision, stating it upfront saves both parties time: \"Licensed physical therapist relocating to Casablanca, seeking a clinical role in sports rehabilitation.\"\n"
"\n"
"The common thread is that an objective works best when there is a gap between your resume and the job that needs to be bridged with explicit context. If your experience already speaks clearly to your fit for the role, a summary will almost always serve you better."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"Despite the rise of AI-powered applicant tracking systems and one-click job applications, cover letters remain one of the most powerful tools in a job seeker's arsenal. Hiring managers consistently report that a well-written cover letter can be the deciding factor between two equally qualified candidates. A cover letter is your opportunity to tell the story that your resume cannot -- it contextualizes your experience, demonstrates your communication skills, and shows genuine interest in the role.\n"
"\n"
"Research from leading recruitment firms shows that roughly 83% of hiring managers read cover letters when they are included with an application. More importantly, 72% of recruiters say they expect a cover letter even when the job posting lists it as optional. Skipping the cover letter can signal a lack of effort or genuine interest in the position, putting you at an immediate disadvantage against candidates who took the time to write one.\n"
"\n"
"The modern cover letter has evolved significantly from the formulaic letters of decades past. Today's most effective cover letters are concise, targeted, and personality-driven. They demonstrate not just what you have done, but how you think, what motivates you, and why this specific role at this specific company is the right fit for your career trajectory. Think of your cover letter as the bridge between your resume and the interview -- it gives you the space to make a compelling case for yourself as a person, not just a list of qualifications.\n"
"\n"
"A strong cover letter also signals professionalism and attention to detail. It shows that you can communicate clearly and persuasively in writing, a skill that is valuable in virtually every industry. Whether you are applying for your first job or making a strategic career move, investing time in your cover letter is one of the highest-return activities in the entire job search process."
msgstr ""

