#: src/data/wiki/categories/job-search-strategies.ts
msgid ""
"Direct outreach to hiring managers is a bold but effective strategy for uncovering hidden opportunities. Many managers have positions they are planning to fill, roles they wish they could create, or problems they need solved but have not yet formalized into a job posting. A well-crafted direct outreach can position you as the solution before the position even exists.\n"
"\n"
"Research your target thoroughly before reaching out. Identify the specific person who would be your direct manager, not just the HR department. Understand the team's current challenges, recent projects, and strategic priorities through LinkedIn, company blogs, conference talks, and press coverage. Your outreach should demonstrate that you understand their world and can add specific value.\n"
"\n"
"Craft a concise outreach message that leads with value rather than need. Instead of \"I am looking for a job,\" try \"I noticed your team recently launched a new data platform, and I have spent the last three years building similar systems at scale. I would love to share some insights from my experience and learn more about your team's roadmap.\" This positions you as a peer offering value rather than a job seeker asking for something.\n"
"\n"
"Keep your initial outreach short, ideally three to four sentences, with a clear and low-commitment call to action. Asking for a \"15-minute conversation\" is more likely to get a response than asking for a \"meeting\" or \"interview.\" Make it easy for the person to say yes by being flexible on timing and format, whether phone, video, or coffee.\n"
"\n"
"Follow up once if you do not receive a response, approximately one week after your initial outreach. If the second message also goes unanswered, move on without taking it personally. Busy professionals receive dozens of messages daily, and a non-response usually reflects their inbox, not their opinion of you. Track these outreach efforts in your application tracker and revisit promising contacts in three to six months when circumstances may have changed."
msgstr ""

