#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-sections.ts
msgid ""
"Each certification entry should include the full certification name, the abbreviation (if commonly used), the issuing organization, and the date earned or the expiration date. For example: \"Project Management Professional (PMP), Project Management Institute, Earned March 2023, Expires March 2026.\"\n"
"\n"
"If the certification does not expire, you can list just the date earned. If it requires ongoing continuing education, note the current status: \"Active\" or \"In Good Standing.\" For certifications you are currently pursuing, write \"In Progress\" or \"Expected [Month Year]\" to signal your commitment without implying you already hold the credential.\n"
"\n"
"Organize multiple certifications in reverse chronological order or by relevance to the target role. If you hold certifications in different domains, you might group them by category: \"Cloud Certifications: AWS Solutions Architect, Azure Administrator\" and \"Security Certifications: CompTIA Security+, CISSP.\"\n"
"\n"
"Include the certification credential ID or verification URL only if it adds value or is commonly expected in your field. Some IT certifications, for example, have public verification portals where employers can confirm your status. Adding \"Credential ID: ABC123\" or \"Verify at [URL]\" adds a layer of credibility.\n"
"\n"
"Keep the section clean and scannable. Use a consistent format for every entry, with clear visual separation between certifications. If you have many certifications, a compact table or column layout can present them efficiently without taking up excessive space."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-formats.ts
msgid ""
"Each resume format has distinct strengths and weaknesses that make it more or less suitable for different situations. Understanding these trade-offs at a glance will help you narrow down your options quickly and confidently.\n"
"\n"
"The chronological format is the most widely accepted and ATS-friendly option. Its strength lies in its familiarity and ability to showcase career progression. It works best for candidates with a consistent work history in a single field and is preferred by most recruiters and hiring managers. Its weakness is that it highlights employment gaps, frequent job changes, and career shifts, making these elements the first things a reviewer notices.\n"
"\n"
"The functional format prioritizes skills over timeline, making it ideal for career changers, individuals re-entering the workforce, and those with non-traditional career paths. Its strength is the ability to group accomplishments by competency, demonstrating your capabilities regardless of when or where you developed them. Its primary weakness is that many recruiters are suspicious of the format and may assume you are hiding something. It also performs poorly with most ATS software.\n"
"\n"
"The combination format merges the skills emphasis of the functional format with the chronological work history that recruiters expect. This makes it versatile and effective for a wide range of candidates, particularly those who want to highlight specific skills while maintaining credibility through a documented work history. Its weakness is that it tends to be longer than other formats and requires more effort to tailor for each application. There is also a risk of content redundancy between the skills and experience sections.\n"
"\n"
"The creative format is a visual approach that uses design elements, color, typography, and layout to create a distinctive resume. It is most effective in creative industries and for roles where visual presentation is valued. Its strength is differentiation: a well-designed creative resume is memorable and demonstrates design skill. Its weakness is limited ATS compatibility and the risk of style overwhelming substance if not executed carefully.\n"
"\n"
"When comparing formats, consider not just their individual merits but how each interacts with your specific situation. A format that is generally considered the best choice might not be the best choice for you. The ideal format is the one that presents your unique combination of skills, experience, and goals in the most compelling light."
msgstr ""

