#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-formats.ts
msgid ""
"Effective creative resume design follows the same fundamental principles that govern all good visual communication. Typography is perhaps the most impactful design element. Choose no more than two complementary typefaces: one for headings and one for body text. Ensure that your body text is at least 10 to 11 points in size for print readability and that your heading hierarchy is clear and consistent. Avoid decorative fonts for body text, as they reduce readability and can feel unprofessional.\n"
"\n"
"Color should be used strategically and sparingly. A one- or two-color accent scheme is typically more effective than a rainbow of colors. Choose colors that reflect your personal brand and the industry you are targeting. Blues and greens convey professionalism and trustworthiness. Bold colors like orange or magenta can signal creativity and energy. Ensure sufficient contrast between text and background for readability, and test your resume in grayscale to confirm it remains effective when printed in black and white.\n"
"\n"
"White space, also known as negative space, is one of the most powerful tools in visual design. Generous margins, consistent spacing between sections, and breathing room around text blocks make your resume feel organized and inviting. Overcrowding a creative resume with too many elements, colors, or text blocks defeats the purpose of the creative format and makes the document feel chaotic.\n"
"\n"
"Visual hierarchy guides the reader's eye through your resume in the order you intend. Use size, weight, color, and position to establish a clear hierarchy. Your name and professional title should be the most prominent elements. Section headings should be clearly differentiated from body text. Important achievements or skills can be highlighted with subtle visual treatments such as bold text, color accents, or icons.\n"
"\n"
"If you include visual elements such as skill bars, icons, charts, or infographics, ensure they are accurate and meaningful. A skill bar showing your proficiency at 85% in Python is only useful if it reflects reality and the reader understands what the scale represents. Avoid purely decorative elements that consume space without conveying information. Every visual element on your resume should earn its place by communicating something about your qualifications.\n"
"\n"
"Consistency is the hallmark of professional design. Ensure that all elements of your resume follow the same stylistic conventions. If you use rounded corners on one graphic element, use them on all similar elements. If your icons are outlined rather than filled, maintain that style throughout. Inconsistencies in design suggest carelessness, which contradicts the message of visual competence that a creative resume is meant to convey."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/remote-work.ts
msgid ""
"Effective digital collaboration goes beyond knowing how to use tools. It requires understanding how to replicate the spontaneous interactions, creative collisions, and team bonding that happen naturally in physical offices. Remote teams that invest in intentional collaboration practices outperform those that rely on tools alone.\n"
"\n"
"Learn to facilitate productive virtual meetings that have clear agendas, defined outcomes, and disciplined time management. The default meeting length should be 25 or 50 minutes rather than 30 or 60, creating natural buffer time between calls. Every meeting should start with a stated objective and end with clear action items and owners. Meetings without agendas or outcomes are the single biggest time waste in remote organizations.\n"
"\n"
"Contribute to team culture and connection through virtual social interactions. Remote teams need intentional social time that would happen organically in an office through lunch conversations, coffee breaks, and hallway chats. Participate actively in virtual coffee chats, team-building activities, and non-work Slack channels. These interactions build the trust and familiarity that make professional collaboration smoother and more enjoyable.\n"
"\n"
"Develop proficiency in collaborative documents and real-time editing tools. The ability to co-author documents in Google Docs, brainstorm in Miro or FigJam, and manage projects in Asana or Linear enables the kind of real-time collaboration that keeps distributed teams moving. Practice these tools regularly so that using them in collaborative sessions feels natural rather than cumbersome.\n"
"\n"
"Give and receive feedback effectively in virtual settings, where tone is easily misunderstood and non-verbal cues are absent. When giving written feedback, lead with positive observations before addressing areas for improvement, use specific examples rather than generalizations, and explicitly separate intent from impact. When receiving feedback, assume positive intent and ask clarifying questions rather than reacting defensively. The written permanence of digital feedback makes thoughtful, constructive communication even more important than in face-to-face interactions."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/job-search-strategies.ts
msgid ""
"Effective follow-up is a strategic communication, not a pestering tactic. The goal is to demonstrate continued interest, provide additional value, and keep your name top of mind without being annoying. The line between persistent and pushy depends entirely on your timing, tone, and the value you add with each touchpoint.\n"
"\n"
"After submitting an application, wait seven to ten business days before your first follow-up. Send a brief email to the hiring manager or recruiter expressing continued interest and offering to provide any additional information. If you can find a relevant connection or talking point, such as a recent company achievement or industry development, weave it in to demonstrate ongoing engagement.\n"
"\n"
"After an interview, send a thank-you email within 24 hours to each person you spoke with. Personalize each email by referencing a specific topic from your conversation. This is not just politeness but a strategic opportunity to reinforce your qualifications, address anything you wish you had said during the interview, and demonstrate your communication skills.\n"
"\n"
"If the employer gave you a timeline for their decision, follow up one to two business days after that deadline passes. A simple message like \"I wanted to check in on the timeline for the X position. I remain very interested and am happy to provide any additional information that would be helpful\" is professional and appropriate. If no timeline was given, follow up one week after the interview.\n"
"\n"
"Track every follow-up in your system with the date sent and the response received. Limit yourself to two to three follow-ups per application before moving it to a \"no response\" status. If three follow-ups over several weeks receive no response, the silence is itself a response, and your energy is better spent on active opportunities. Keep these contacts in your tracker in case the company reaches out later, which happens more often than you might expect."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/job-search-strategies.ts
msgid ""
"Effective networking for job searching is not about collecting business cards or LinkedIn connections. It is about building genuine professional relationships where both parties derive value. The most powerful job search networks are built over months and years through consistent engagement, mutual support, and authentic professional interest.\n"
"\n"
"Start by mapping your existing network more thoroughly than you think necessary. First-degree connections include former colleagues, classmates, professors, mentors, neighbors, family friends, and members of professional organizations you belong to. Second-degree connections include the contacts of your first-degree connections, which exponentially expands your reach. Research shows that a disproportionate number of job opportunities come through weak ties, the acquaintances and distant connections who travel in different professional circles than your close contacts.\n"
"\n"
"Reach out to your network with a specific and reasonable ask rather than a vague \"I am looking for a job.\" A message like \"I am exploring senior product management roles in fintech and noticed you are connected to the VP of Product at Company X. Would you be comfortable making an introduction?\" gives your contact a clear, actionable way to help that requires minimal effort on their part.\n"
"\n"
"Give before you ask. Share relevant articles, make introductions, congratulate contacts on achievements, and offer your expertise when it could be helpful. People are significantly more likely to help someone who has demonstrated generosity and genuine interest in the relationship. If your first outreach in five years is asking for a job referral, you have started the relationship on an imbalanced footing.\n"
"\n"
"Attend industry events, conferences, meetups, and professional association meetings regularly, not just when you are actively job searching. The relationships built during these interactions create the network infrastructure that supports you when opportunities arise. Virtual events and online communities have made it possible to build a robust professional network regardless of geographic location."
msgstr ""

