#: src/data/wiki/categories/industry-guides.ts
msgid "Finance & Accounting Resume Guide"
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/industry-guides.ts
msgid ""
"Finance and accounting are precision-driven fields where accuracy, analytical rigor, and attention to detail are not just valued; they are required. The way you present your resume is itself an evaluation of these qualities. A finance resume with formatting inconsistencies, vague claims, or unquantified accomplishments sends a contradictory message about your professional standards. Hiring managers in banking, corporate finance, public accounting, and financial analysis hold resumes to an exceptionally high standard because the work itself demands exceptional standards.\n"
"\n"
"The finance industry encompasses a broad spectrum of roles with distinct evaluation criteria. An investment banking analyst resume is judged differently from a corporate controller resume, which differs from a financial planning and analysis resume or a public accounting resume. However, certain expectations are universal: demonstrated quantitative ability, evidence of working with financial data at scale, knowledge of relevant regulations and standards, and a track record of contributing to financial outcomes. Your resume must address these universal expectations while also tailoring its emphasis to the specific subsector you are targeting.\n"
"\n"
"Finance hiring processes are also known for being highly competitive and structured. Major firms receive thousands of applications for each open position, and the initial screening is often performed by junior HR staff or automated systems that filter based on specific criteria such as educational institution, GPA, certifications, and years of relevant experience. Understanding these screening mechanisms and optimizing your resume accordingly is not optional; it is a prerequisite for getting your application in front of a hiring manager who can evaluate your substantive qualifications."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/industry-guides.ts
msgid ""
"Finance resumes follow stricter formatting conventions than most other industries. The expectation is a clean, conservative document that prioritizes substance over style. Use a traditional serif or sans-serif font, black text on white background, and minimal design elements. The finance industry values conformity in presentation because it signals awareness of professional norms and attention to the details that matter.\n"
"\n"
"For most finance professionals, the resume should be one page unless you have more than ten to twelve years of experience with genuinely diverse and relevant roles. Investment banking resumes are almost always one page regardless of experience level, as the culture prizes conciseness and the ability to communicate complex information efficiently. Accounting and corporate finance professionals with extensive experience may extend to two pages, but every line must earn its place through relevant content.\n"
"\n"
"Use reverse chronological format, leading with your most recent experience. Each position entry should include the company name, your title, location, and dates of employment. Bullet points under each role should be concise, achievement-oriented, and quantified. Avoid paragraphs or lengthy narratives in the experience section. The standard in finance is three to five tight bullet points per role that each communicate a distinct accomplishment or responsibility.\n"
"\n"
"Pay particular attention to consistency in formatting financial figures and dates. Use a consistent number format throughout, either spelling out numbers or using numerals, and apply the same treatment to currency figures, percentages, and dates. Inconsistencies in these elements are more noticeable on a finance resume than on any other type of document, and they can undermine your credibility with detail-oriented reviewers. Before submitting, review your resume specifically for formatting consistency, as this quality check mirrors the review discipline expected in financial reporting and analysis."
msgstr ""

