#: src/data/wiki/categories/industry-guides.ts
msgid "For entry-level and early-career finance positions, especially in investment banking, consulting, and Big Four accounting, include your GPA if it is 3.3 or higher. Many finance employers have explicit GPA cutoffs for campus recruiting. After three to five years of professional experience, GPA becomes less relevant and can be removed unless it was exceptionally high or you are applying to firms known to value academic credentials throughout an employee's career."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-sections.ts
msgid ""
"For entry-level candidates, a summary might read: \"Recent finance graduate from ISCAE Casablanca with internship experience in corporate auditing and a strong foundation in IFRS standards. Completed a capstone project analyzing risk portfolios for three Moroccan banks, delivering findings that were adopted by the supervising team.\"\n"
"\n"
"Mid-career professionals can leverage more depth: \"Operations manager with seven years of experience in logistics and supply chain optimization across the MENA region. Led a warehouse automation initiative that reduced order fulfillment time by 28 percent and saved $1.2 million annually. Fluent in Arabic, French, and English.\"\n"
"\n"
"Senior and executive candidates should emphasize leadership scope: \"Chief Technology Officer with 15 years of experience building engineering organizations from startup to scale-up. Grew a team from 12 to 180 engineers across four countries while maintaining a 92 percent employee retention rate. Led the platform migration that increased system throughput by 400 percent.\"\n"
"\n"
"Career changers face a unique challenge. Focus on transferable skills and the narrative bridge: \"Former high school mathematics teacher transitioning into data science, combining six years of quantitative problem-solving with newly earned certifications in machine learning and statistical analysis. Built predictive models during a bootcamp capstone that achieved 94 percent accuracy on real-world datasets.\""
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/industry-guides.ts
msgid ""
"For entry-level candidates, the resume should be exactly one page. This is not merely a convention; it is an expectation. Hiring managers reviewing entry-level applications expect a concise, focused document, and a two-page resume from a recent graduate signals poor editing judgment rather than extensive experience. If you are struggling to fill a single page, it likely means you are not fully leveraging your academic projects, volunteer work, and transferable skills. If you are exceeding one page, it means you are including unnecessary detail or irrelevant information.\n"
"\n"
"Choose a clean, professional format with clear section headers, consistent formatting, and adequate white space. Avoid creative designs, unusual fonts, or color schemes unless you are applying for design roles where visual creativity is part of the evaluation. Use a standard font such as Calibri, Arial, or Garamond at ten to twelve points. Maintain consistent margins between one-half and one inch on all sides. These formatting choices may seem minor, but they directly affect readability and convey professionalism.\n"
"\n"
"The most common entry-level resume mistakes include listing job duties instead of accomplishments, including a high school education when you have a college degree, using an unprofessional email address, and failing to proofread for spelling and grammar errors. Additionally, many entry-level candidates make the mistake of including irrelevant personal information such as hobbies, age, or marital status. Unless a hobby directly relates to the role you are targeting or demonstrates a notable achievement, it does not belong on your resume.\n"
"\n"
"Another frequent error is submitting the same generic resume for every application. Entry-level candidates often assume that since they have limited experience, there is nothing to tailor. This assumption is incorrect. You should adjust your professional summary, reorder your skills to match the job posting, and emphasize the experiences most relevant to each specific role. Even small adjustments can significantly improve your match rate with both applicant tracking systems and human reviewers who can tell when a candidate has taken the time to align their application with the position."
msgstr ""

#: src/routes/builder/$resumeId/-sidebar/right/sections/notes.tsx
msgid "For example, information regarding which companies you sent this resume to or the links to the job descriptions can be noted down here."
msgstr "Par exemple, des informations sur les entreprises auxquelles vous avez envoyé ce CV ou les liens vers les descriptions de poste peuvent être notées ici."

#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"For freelancers, a portfolio is not just a nice-to-have; it is an essential companion to your resume. While your resume provides the narrative and metrics, a portfolio provides the tangible evidence that brings your claims to life.\n"
"\n"
"Create a professional online portfolio that showcases your best work. Organize it by project type, industry, or skill set, whichever is most relevant to the full-time roles you are targeting. Each portfolio piece should include a brief description of the project, your role, the challenge you addressed, and the outcome you achieved. If possible, include client testimonials that speak to both the quality of your work and your professional demeanor.\n"
"\n"
"For fields where confidential work prevents you from showing actual client deliverables, create case studies that describe your process and results without revealing sensitive information. You can also create personal projects that demonstrate your skills independently of client work. A developer might contribute to open source projects, a designer might redesign a well-known app as a concept exercise, or a writer might maintain a professional blog.\n"
"\n"
"Include your portfolio URL prominently on your resume, typically in the header alongside your contact information. Many hiring managers will visit your portfolio before they finish reading your resume, so make sure it loads quickly, looks professional, and showcases work relevant to the role you are pursuing.\n"
"\n"
"Keep your portfolio updated and curated. It should feature your strongest 10 to 15 pieces of work, not an exhaustive catalog of everything you have ever created. Quality over quantity signals confidence and good judgment. Remove older work that no longer represents your current skill level, and regularly add new pieces that demonstrate growth and relevance to your target roles."
msgstr ""

