#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"Just as there are proven strategies for strong openings, there are well-known pitfalls that immediately signal a weak application. Recognizing and avoiding these cliches is just as important as knowing what works.\n"
"\n"
"Never open with \"I am writing to apply for the position of...\" This is the single most overused cover letter opening in existence, and it wastes your most valuable real estate on information the hiring manager already knows. They know you are writing to apply -- they are reading your application. Use those precious opening words to say something meaningful instead.\n"
"\n"
"Avoid generic enthusiasm that could apply to any company: \"I am very excited about the opportunity to work for your dynamic and innovative company.\" This tells the hiring manager nothing about why you are specifically interested in their organization. If your opening could be copied and pasted into a letter for any company in the same industry, it is too generic.\n"
"\n"
"Do not lead with your own needs or desires: \"I am seeking a challenging position where I can grow my skills and advance my career.\" The employer's primary concern is what you can do for them, not what they can do for you. While career growth is a legitimate motivation, leading with it in your opening makes the letter feel self-centered.\n"
"\n"
"Avoid self-deprecating or apologetic openings: \"Although I may not have all the qualifications listed, I believe I could be a good fit...\" This immediately positions you as an underqualified candidate and gives the hiring manager a reason to stop reading. Even if you do not meet every requirement, lead with your strengths and let the reader discover any gaps themselves.\n"
"\n"
"Humor and cleverness should be deployed cautiously in cover letter openings. While a well-placed, relevant quip can be memorable, forced humor or irrelevant anecdotes will fall flat. The safest approach is to be engaging and personable without trying to be funny. If humor comes naturally in the context of a relevant story, that is fine -- but never sacrifice professionalism for a laugh."
msgstr ""

