#: src/data/wiki/categories/interview-preparation.ts
msgid ""
"Many candidates underestimate the importance of post-interview follow-up, but it can be the decisive factor that separates you from equally qualified competitors. According to hiring surveys, a significant percentage of hiring managers expect to receive a thank you note after an interview, and many report that the absence of one negatively influences their hiring decision. A thoughtful follow-up demonstrates professionalism, attention to detail, and genuine interest in the role, qualities that every employer values.\n"
"\n"
"The follow-up is also your opportunity to address anything you wish you had said during the interview. Perhaps you forgot to mention a relevant project, or you thought of a better answer to a tough question on your drive home. A follow-up email gives you a second chance to make those points. It also allows you to clarify any responses that may not have come across as clearly as you intended, turning a potential weakness into a strength.\n"
"\n"
"Beyond the immediate impact on your candidacy, consistent follow-up behavior builds your professional reputation over time. Even if you do not get this particular job, a gracious and well-written thank you note can keep you in the employer's mind for future opportunities. Hiring managers often keep a mental or physical list of impressive candidates who were not selected for a specific role but would be great fits for other positions.\n"
"\n"
"The follow-up process also gives you valuable information about the employer. How they respond to your follow-up communication reveals a lot about their culture and professionalism. An organization that acknowledges your thank you note promptly and keeps you informed about the timeline is likely one that values communication and respect. This information helps you make a more informed decision if and when an offer arrives."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-sections.ts
msgid "Many companies restrict official references to confirming only job title and dates of employment. In these cases, your former supervisor may still be willing to provide a personal reference separate from the company's official policy. Contact them directly and ask if they would be comfortable giving an individual reference. Most are happy to help, especially if you had a positive working relationship."
msgstr ""

#: src/routes/dashboard/tools/-components/salary-calculator-components.tsx
msgid "Many jobs"
msgstr "Nombreux emplois"

#: src/data/wiki/categories/salary-negotiation.ts
msgid ""
"Many professionals focus exclusively on base salary during negotiations, overlooking the benefits and perks that can represent 30 to 50 percent of total compensation value. Benefits negotiation is often easier than salary negotiation because many companies have rigid salary bands but significant flexibility on other compensation components. A hiring manager who cannot add another ten thousand to your base salary may have the authority to offer a signing bonus, additional equity, extra vacation days, or a flexible work arrangement.\n"
"\n"
"The tax efficiency of certain benefits makes them even more valuable than their face value suggests. Employer contributions to retirement plans, health insurance premiums, and pre-tax benefits like commuter allowances and HSA contributions reduce your taxable income. A benefit worth five thousand dollars in pre-tax contributions could be worth more to you than a five thousand dollar salary increase after taxes.\n"
"\n"
"Benefits also have compounding career value. A professional development budget that funds certifications and conference attendance increases your skills and market value. A flexible work arrangement reduces commuting costs and time while improving quality of life. Equity that vests over time aligns your financial interests with the company's success and can produce life-changing returns in high-growth companies.\n"
"\n"
"Understanding the full landscape of negotiable benefits puts you in a much stronger position. Even if base salary is truly fixed, the right combination of benefits can close a significant gap between the offer and your expectations."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/remote-work.ts
msgid "Many remote skills are transferable from other contexts. Experience managing distributed projects, communicating with remote clients, maintaining productivity while traveling, or contributing to open-source projects all demonstrate remote competency. You can also build remote skills through online courses, virtual volunteer work, or freelance projects completed in a distributed team environment."
