#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"Military service develops leadership and interpersonal skills that are exceptionally valuable in the civilian workplace, but veterans often undersell these abilities because they seem like basic expectations in the military context.\n"
"\n"
"In the civilian world, the ability to lead a team under pressure, make decisions with incomplete information, adapt to rapidly changing circumstances, and maintain composure in high-stakes situations is highly valued and relatively rare. Veterans possess these skills as a matter of course, having been trained and tested in environments far more demanding than most civilian workplaces.\n"
"\n"
"Frame your leadership experience in terms of outcomes and scale. Rather than saying you \"led a squad,\" describe how you \"directed a team of 12 professionals across multiple projects, achieving a 98 percent on-time delivery rate while maintaining team morale and professional development.\" This conveys the same experience but in terms that resonate with civilian hiring managers.\n"
"\n"
"Highlight your experience with diversity and cross-cultural communication. Military service often involves working with people from vastly different backgrounds and in multicultural environments. This experience is directly relevant to today's global and diverse workplace. Describe specific instances where you navigated cultural differences, built cohesive teams from diverse groups, or operated effectively in unfamiliar cultural contexts.\n"
"\n"
"Do not overlook the mentoring and training aspects of your military service. If you trained new personnel, developed training curricula, or mentored junior service members, these experiences translate directly to coaching, training and development, and people management roles in the civilian sector. Many veterans have more formal training experience than civilian candidates with comparable years in the workforce."
msgstr ""

