msgstr "Situation militaire"

#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid "Military to Civilian Resume: Translation Guide"
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"Military veterans possess some of the most impressive leadership, organizational, and technical skills in the workforce, yet many struggle to communicate these skills effectively on a civilian resume. The fundamental challenge is one of translation: military experience is rich with specialized terminology, rank structures, and operational concepts that civilian hiring managers may not understand.\n"
"\n"
"When a veteran writes \"Served as E-7 responsible for the readiness and welfare of a 45-person platoon across three FOBs in support of OEF,\" they are describing a high-level management role with enormous responsibility. But a civilian recruiter who has never served may not know what E-7 means, what a FOB is, or what OEF stands for. The experience is genuinely impressive, but the language creates a barrier.\n"
"\n"
"The goal of a military-to-civilian resume is not to hide your service or pretend you were in a corporate environment. It is to present your military achievements in a way that civilian employers can immediately understand and appreciate. This means replacing jargon with plain language, translating military roles into civilian equivalents, and focusing on the universal skills and measurable outcomes that every employer values.\n"
"\n"
"Veterans also need to overcome the misconception that military experience only prepares you for security or law enforcement roles. The skills developed in military service, including leadership, logistics, technology, healthcare, engineering, communications, and strategic planning, are directly applicable to virtually every civilian industry."
msgstr ""

