#: src/data/wiki/categories/job-search-strategies.ts
msgid ""
"Most job seekers use basic keyword searches and miss the advanced search features that dramatically improve result quality. Boolean search operators work on most major job boards and allow you to create precise search queries. Use AND to require multiple terms, OR to include alternatives, NOT or a minus sign to exclude terms, and quotation marks for exact phrases.\n"
"\n"
"For example, searching for \"product manager\" AND (SaaS OR \"B2B software\") NOT junior filters results to SaaS or B2B software product manager roles while excluding junior positions. This single search replaces dozens of simpler searches and produces much more relevant results.\n"
"\n"
"Location-based filtering goes beyond simple city searches on most platforms. Indeed, LinkedIn, and Glassdoor all allow radius searches, remote-only filters, and multi-location searches. If you are open to several cities, set up separate alerts for each rather than a single broad search, as this often surfaces different results and prevents the algorithm from defaulting to the largest metro area.\n"
"\n"
"Salary filtering, when available, helps you avoid wasting time on positions below your range. Indeed and Glassdoor both offer salary estimate filters. While these estimates are not always accurate, they help eliminate clearly mismatched opportunities. Many states and cities now require salary transparency in job postings, making salary filtering increasingly reliable.\n"
"\n"
"Save your advanced searches and set up alerts rather than re-running them manually. Most platforms allow you to save complex search queries and receive daily or weekly email digests of new matches. This automated approach ensures you never miss a relevant posting while freeing up time for higher-value activities like networking and application tailoring.\n"
"\n"
"Use the company follow feature on LinkedIn and Glassdoor to track your target companies. When a company you follow posts a new position, you receive an alert immediately, often before the position appears in general search results. Build a follow list of 20 to 50 companies you would be excited to work for, and you will have an early-mover advantage on their postings."
msgstr ""

