#: src/data/wiki/categories/job-search-strategies.ts
msgid ""
"Recruiters and staffing agencies are professional gatekeepers to the hidden job market, particularly for mid-senior level positions. Understanding how the recruiter ecosystem works helps you leverage it effectively. There are two main types: retained search firms that work on exclusive assignments for senior positions, and contingency recruiters who fill multiple roles simultaneously and are paid only when their candidate is hired.\n"
"\n"
"Build relationships with two to three recruiters who specialize in your industry and level. A recruiter who understands your target roles, compensation expectations, and career goals becomes a valuable long-term partner who proactively presents you for relevant opportunities as they arise. The best recruiter relationships are built over years, not initiated during an active search.\n"
"\n"
"When working with recruiters, be honest about your situation, timeline, and expectations. Recruiters work most effectively when they have accurate information about your requirements. If you are only interested in remote roles above a certain salary, say so clearly rather than wasting both parties' time on mismatched opportunities.\n"
"\n"
"Remember that recruiters work for the employer, not for you. Their incentive is to fill the position, which aligns with your interests when the role is a good fit, but may not align when the recruiter is trying to fill a role that does not match your criteria. Evaluate every opportunity on its merits rather than accepting a position simply because a recruiter presented it enthusiastically.\n"
"\n"
"Maintain your recruiter relationships even when you are not actively searching. A periodic check-in, sharing industry news, or referring colleagues who might be a good fit for roles the recruiter is filling keeps you top of mind. When the recruiter encounters a position that matches your profile, you want to be the first person they call."
msgstr ""

