#: src/routes/dashboard/tools/negotiation.tsx
msgid "Salary Negotiation Guide"
msgstr "Guide de négociation salariale"

#: src/data/wiki/categories/salary-negotiation.ts
msgid ""
"Salary negotiation is fundamentally a psychological exercise, and understanding the mental dynamics at play gives you a significant advantage. The most important psychological principle to internalize is that negotiation is expected. Hiring managers budget for it, HR departments build negotiation room into their offers, and candidates who negotiate are often respected more than those who simply accept the first number.\n"
"\n"
"The fear of negotiation is the biggest obstacle most professionals face. Research from Carnegie Mellon shows that only about 30 percent of job candidates negotiate their initial offer, meaning the majority leave money on the table. This fear typically stems from the misconception that negotiating will cause the offer to be rescinded, which happens in less than one percent of cases when done professionally.\n"
"\n"
"Confidence in negotiation comes from preparation, not personality. Introverts negotiate just as effectively as extroverts when they have solid research, clear goals, and practiced scripts. The key is reframing the negotiation from a confrontation to a collaborative problem-solving conversation. You and the employer both want to reach an agreement. The negotiation is simply the process of finding terms that work for everyone.\n"
"\n"
"Emotional regulation is critical during the negotiation process. When you receive an offer, resist the urge to respond immediately, whether your instinct is to accept excitedly or react with disappointment. Taking time to evaluate an offer is professional and expected. A simple \"Thank you for this offer. I am very excited about the opportunity and would like a couple of days to review the full package\" gives you the space to think strategically rather than react emotionally."
msgstr ""

