#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"Several common closing paragraph mistakes can undermine the strong impression you have built throughout your letter. Being aware of these pitfalls ensures your letter ends on the highest possible note.\n"
"\n"
"Never close with desperation or excessive gratitude. Phrases like \"I really need this job\" or \"I would be eternally grateful for even a chance to interview\" may seem humble, but they project insecurity and can make the hiring manager uncomfortable. Confidence is far more attractive than desperation in a professional context.\n"
"\n"
"Avoid introducing new information or qualifications in your closing paragraph. The closing is for summarizing and looking forward, not for cramming in additional details you forgot to mention earlier. If you realize there is an important qualification you did not cover, revise your body paragraphs to include it rather than tacking it onto the end.\n"
"\n"
"Do not make demands or set conditions in your closing. Mentioning salary requirements, work-from-home preferences, or scheduling constraints in your cover letter closing is premature and can disqualify you before you even get to the negotiation stage. Save these discussions for when you have an offer or are deep in the interview process.\n"
"\n"
"Resist the urge to over-promise. Statements like \"I guarantee I will exceed all of your expectations\" or \"You will not find a better candidate\" sound arrogant and set unrealistic expectations. Instead, express confidence in what you have already demonstrated through your achievements and experience.\n"
"\n"
"Finally, never forget to actually include a call to action. A surprisingly large number of cover letters simply end with \"Thank you for your time\" and a sign-off, leaving the next steps entirely ambiguous. Every cover letter should end with a clear invitation to continue the conversation, giving the hiring manager a gentle nudge toward reaching out to schedule an interview."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/job-search-strategies.ts
msgid ""
"Several dedicated tools have been built specifically for job search tracking and offer features that spreadsheets cannot match. Huntr, Teal, and JobHero are popular options that provide Kanban-style boards, browser extensions that auto-capture job posting details, and built-in follow-up reminders. These tools reduce manual data entry and provide more intuitive visual management of your pipeline.\n"
"\n"
"Browser extensions from these platforms allow you to save job postings with a single click while browsing any job board. The extension automatically captures the company name, position title, location, and posting URL, eliminating the manual copy-paste workflow that makes spreadsheet tracking tedious. Some extensions even parse the job description and extract key requirements for easy reference.\n"
"\n"
"CRM-style tools like Streak for Gmail or HubSpot's free CRM can be repurposed for job search tracking, particularly if you value email integration. These tools track your email correspondence with each company, remind you to follow up after set periods, and provide analytics on your outreach patterns. The email tracking features show you when recruiters open your messages, which helps you time follow-up communications.\n"
"\n"
"Choose a tool based on your personal workflow rather than feature lists. The best tracking system is the one you will actually use consistently. If you already live in Google Sheets, a spreadsheet may be more practical than a dedicated app. If you are a visual thinker, a Kanban board tool might suit your style better. Test two or three options during the first week of your search and commit to one.\n"
"\n"
"Regardless of which tool you choose, ensure it supports mobile access so you can update it immediately after interviews, networking conversations, or recruiter calls. Logging details in the moment while they are fresh in your memory is far more accurate and efficient than trying to reconstruct the conversation hours or days later."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-formats.ts
msgid ""
"Several persistent myths surround the functional resume format, and understanding the truth behind them is essential for making an informed decision about your resume strategy. One common myth is that functional resumes are universally rejected by employers. While it is true that some recruiters prefer chronological formats, a well-crafted functional resume can still be effective, particularly in industries that value skills and creativity over rigid career timelines. Creative fields, startups, and non-profit organizations may be more receptive to non-traditional formats.\n"
"\n"
"Another myth is that functional resumes are only for people who are trying to hide something. While the format does de-emphasize your work timeline, using it does not automatically signal dishonesty. Many legitimate scenarios call for a skills-first approach, including career transitions, military-to-civilian moves, and returns from extended education. The key is to be transparent in your professional summary about your situation and to include a brief but honest work history section.\n"
"\n"
"Some job seekers believe that a functional resume means they do not need to include any work history at all. This is a misconception that can seriously hurt your chances. Omitting your work history entirely will almost certainly raise red flags. Even in a functional format, you should include a concise employment section with job titles, company names, and dates. The difference is that this section takes a supporting role rather than being the centerpiece of your resume.\n"
"\n"
"There is also a myth that functional resumes perform well with applicant tracking systems because they can be loaded with keywords. While you can certainly include relevant keywords in your skills sections, ATS software relies on parsing structured data that includes job titles matched with dates and companies. A functional resume disrupts this structure, which can lead to parsing errors and lower match scores regardless of how many keywords you include.\n"
"\n"
"Finally, some candidates believe that a functional resume is always the best choice for career changers. While it can be effective, many career counselors now recommend the combination format instead. The combination format allows you to lead with your transferable skills while still providing the chronological work history that recruiters expect. This hybrid approach gives you the best of both worlds and avoids the skepticism that sometimes accompanies purely functional resumes."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/salary-negotiation.ts
msgid ""
"Several powerful tools can help you build a comprehensive picture of compensation for your target role. Glassdoor remains one of the most widely used platforms, offering salary reports based on employee submissions that include base pay, bonuses, and total compensation breakdowns by company, location, and experience level. While individual data points may vary, the aggregated ranges provide valuable benchmarks.\n"
"\n"
"LinkedIn Salary Insights leverages data from its massive professional network to provide compensation ranges filtered by title, location, industry, and experience. The platform also shows how factors like education and skills correlate with pay variations, giving you a multidimensional view of compensation drivers.\n"
"\n"
"The Bureau of Labor Statistics Occupational Outlook Handbook provides government-collected data on median pay, job growth projections, and industry-specific compensation trends. While this data tends to lag behind real-time market conditions, it provides a reliable baseline and is particularly useful for understanding long-term compensation trajectories.\n"
"\n"
"Levels.fyi has become the gold standard for technology compensation research, offering verified compensation data that breaks down total packages into base salary, stock grants, and bonuses. Payscale and Salary.com use compensation surveys to provide detailed reports factoring in cost of living, certifications, and specialized skills. Compensation consulting firms like Robert Half and Hays publish annual salary guides by industry and role that are particularly valuable for specialized positions.\n"
"\n"
"Professional associations and industry groups often conduct their own compensation surveys that provide the most granular data for specific career paths. The IEEE, AMA, SHRM, and similar organizations publish annual reports that break down compensation by sub-specialty, years of experience, certifications, and geographic market."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-formats.ts
msgid "Several tools can help you create professional creative resumes. Resume builders like IMTA Resume offer beautifully designed templates that balance creativity with ATS compatibility. For more custom designs, tools like Canva, Figma, and Adobe InDesign provide full creative control. If you are comfortable with web technologies, you can build your resume as a responsive web page using HTML and CSS. Choose a tool that matches your design skill level to avoid creating something that looks amateur."
msgstr ""

