#: src/data/wiki/categories/industry-guides.ts
msgid ""
"Skilled trades and technical positions are evaluated on criteria that differ substantially from white-collar professional roles. While office-based jobs emphasize educational credentials, analytical thinking, and communication skills, trades employers prioritize hands-on capability, safety awareness, certifications, reliability, and the ability to work in demanding physical environments. A resume that excels in a corporate hiring process will likely fall flat when submitted for an electrician, HVAC technician, welder, or maintenance mechanic position.\n"
"\n"
"The skilled trades are experiencing significant labor shortages across most developed economies, which means qualified candidates are in high demand. However, this demand does not mean that any resume will get you hired. Employers in construction, manufacturing, utilities, and maintenance are dealing with high-stakes work environments where hiring mistakes can lead to equipment damage, project delays, safety incidents, and regulatory violations. They need resumes that quickly and clearly demonstrate the candidate's qualifications, certifications, and practical experience.\n"
"\n"
"Trade resumes must communicate competence through specificity. Employers want to know exactly which systems you have worked on, which tools and equipment you are proficient with, which safety protocols you follow, and what scope of work you have handled independently versus under supervision. This guide provides the framework for building a trades resume that speaks directly to what hiring managers and foremen are looking for when they need to fill critical positions on their crews and teams."
msgstr ""

