#: src/data/wiki/categories/remote-work.ts
msgid ""
"Technical failures happen, and how you handle them reveals your composure and problem-solving ability. If your video freezes, internet drops, or audio fails, stay calm and follow your backup plan. Keep the interviewer's phone number or email accessible so you can quickly communicate if the connection is lost. A message like \"I apologize for the technical difficulty. My internet dropped. Shall I rejoin the same link or would a phone call work better?\" demonstrates professionalism under pressure.\n"
"\n"
"Background interruptions from pets, children, delivery drivers, or roommates are a reality of remote work, and interviewers understand this. If an interruption occurs, address it briefly and calmly rather than pretending it did not happen. Acknowledge it with humor if appropriate: \"I apologize, my dog apparently also wants to interview for this role.\" Then quickly refocus on the conversation. Handling an interruption gracefully demonstrates the adaptability that remote work requires.\n"
"\n"
"Time zone confusion is a common virtual interview pitfall. Always confirm the interview time with the specific time zone in your confirmation message. Set reminders for 30 minutes and 10 minutes before the interview. If the interviewer is in a different time zone, acknowledge it and verify the time at least 24 hours in advance.\n"
"\n"
"Screen sharing during technical interviews or presentations can be stressful because the interviewer sees everything on your screen. Before the interview, close all unnecessary applications, browser tabs, and notification sources. Disable desktop notifications from email, messaging apps, and social media. Use your video platform's screen share feature to share a specific window rather than your entire desktop when possible.\n"
"\n"
"Multi-person panel interviews are more challenging in virtual format because you cannot read the room's collective energy. Address panelists by name when responding to their questions and make an effort to distribute your eye contact, or camera contact, across different questioners rather than focusing exclusively on the person who asked the most recent question. After the interview, send individualized thank-you messages to each panelist."
msgstr ""

#: src/routes/dashboard/interview/-components/outfit-config.ts
#~ msgid "Technical Interview"
#~ msgstr "Entretien technique"

#: src/data/wiki/categories/interview-preparation.ts
msgid ""
"Technical interview questions vary widely depending on the industry and role, but the underlying principles for answering them remain consistent. Whether you are asked to solve a coding challenge, analyze a case study, or explain a complex concept, the interviewer is evaluating both your technical knowledge and your ability to communicate that knowledge clearly. Always think aloud during technical questions, as interviewers want to understand your reasoning process, not just your final answer.\n"
"\n"
"For roles in technology, expect questions about data structures, algorithms, system design, and language-specific features. The best preparation involves practicing with real problems on platforms like LeetCode or HackerRank while explaining your approach as if you were in an interview. For roles in finance, marketing, or consulting, prepare for case study questions that require you to analyze business scenarios and recommend strategies. Structure your analysis using established frameworks and support your recommendations with data.\n"
"\n"
"Industry-specific knowledge questions test whether you understand the fundamentals of the field. For example, a marketing candidate might be asked to explain the difference between earned and paid media, while an accounting candidate might be asked about revenue recognition principles. Review the core concepts of your field and be prepared to discuss recent trends, regulations, or innovations that could affect the organization.\n"
"\n"
"When you encounter a technical question you cannot answer, honesty is always the best approach. Acknowledge what you do not know while demonstrating your problem-solving process. You might say \"I have not worked directly with that technology, but based on my experience with similar tools, I would approach it by...\" This shows intellectual humility, adaptability, and a willingness to learn, all qualities that employers value."
msgstr ""

#: src/routes/dashboard/interview/-components/voice-interview-config.ts
msgid "Technical Lead"
msgstr "Responsable technique"

#: src/routes/dashboard/networking/-components/recommendation-request-config.ts
msgid "Technical mastery"
msgstr "Maîtrise technique"

#: src/data/wiki/categories/industry-guides.ts
msgid ""
"Technical proficiency has become a critical differentiator in finance hiring. While fundamental accounting knowledge and financial acumen remain essential, the ability to work efficiently with financial software, build robust analytical models, and leverage data analysis tools increasingly separates competitive candidates from average ones. Your resume should clearly articulate your technical capabilities to demonstrate readiness for the analytical demands of modern finance roles.\n"
"\n"
"Microsoft Excel remains the foundational tool of finance, but listing basic Excel as a skill communicates nothing. Instead, specify your advanced Excel competencies: pivot tables, VLOOKUP and INDEX-MATCH functions, data validation, conditional formatting, VBA macro development, Power Query for data transformation, and complex financial modeling using scenario and sensitivity analysis. If you have built specific types of models, such as discounted cash flow valuations, leveraged buyout models, merger models, or budget forecasting templates, mention these by name as they signal direct relevance to specific role types.\n"
"\n"
"Beyond Excel, list the specialized financial software platforms you have experience with. For accounting roles, this includes ERP systems such as SAP, Oracle, NetSuite, and Sage, as well as specialized tools like Hyperion, Workiva, and BlackLine. For banking and investment roles, include Bloomberg Terminal, FactSet, Capital IQ, PitchBook, and any deal management or portfolio management platforms. For audit and tax, mention audit management software, tax preparation platforms such as CCH or UltraTax, and data analytics tools used in audit procedures.\n"
"\n"
"Data analysis and programming skills are increasingly valued across all finance functions. Python, SQL, R, and Tableau are the most commonly sought technical skills beyond traditional finance tools. If you have used Python for financial analysis, automated reporting processes with SQL queries, built dashboards in Tableau or Power BI, or used R for statistical analysis, include these skills and describe how you applied them in a financial context. The combination of financial domain expertise with technical data skills is one of the most powerful differentiators in the current finance job market and commands premium compensation."
msgstr ""

