#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"The body of your cover letter is where you make your case. This is not the place for vague claims or generic statements about being a \"hard worker\" or a \"team player.\" Instead, focus on specific, quantifiable achievements that demonstrate your ability to deliver results in the areas most relevant to the target role.\n"
"\n"
"Use the STAR method (Situation, Task, Action, Result) as a framework for structuring your examples. For instance, rather than saying \"I have experience in digital marketing,\" write something like: \"At my previous role with Meridian Analytics, I redesigned the email marketing strategy for our enterprise clients, implementing segmentation and personalization that increased open rates by 45% and generated an additional $2.3 million in annual recurring revenue.\" This level of specificity is far more compelling than general claims.\n"
"\n"
"Choose two or three examples that directly align with the most important requirements listed in the job description. If the role emphasizes leadership, describe a situation where you led a team through a challenging project. If it requires technical skills, highlight a complex problem you solved using those specific technologies. The goal is to make it effortless for the reader to see the connection between your past performance and their current needs.\n"
"\n"
"Do not simply repeat what is on your resume. Your cover letter should complement your resume by providing context, narrative, and personality that a bulleted list cannot capture. Explain why you made certain career decisions, what you learned from key experiences, and how those lessons have prepared you for this specific opportunity. This storytelling approach creates a memorable impression that distinguishes you from other applicants.\n"
"\n"
"When discussing your qualifications, strike a balance between confidence and humility. You want to present yourself as capable and accomplished without coming across as arrogant. Phrases like \"I am proud of my track record in...\" or \"My experience has taught me that...\" convey competence while remaining approachable."
msgstr ""

