#: src/data/wiki/categories/industry-guides.ts
msgid ""
"The education section of an engineering resume carries different weight depending on your career stage. For new graduates and early-career engineers with fewer than three years of experience, education is often the strongest section and should be placed prominently. Include your degree, institution, graduation date, relevant coursework, academic projects, and GPA if it is above a 3.5 on a 4.0 scale. Capstone projects and thesis work are particularly valuable as they demonstrate your ability to scope, execute, and deliver complex technical work.\n"
"\n"
"For experienced engineers, education typically moves below the experience section and can be condensed to degree, institution, and graduation year. Advanced degrees such as a Master's in Computer Science or a specialized engineering discipline remain relevant throughout your career and should always be included. If you completed your degree while working full-time, noting this can demonstrate time management and dedication, though it is not required.\n"
"\n"
"Certifications in engineering carry varying weight depending on the subdomain. Cloud certifications from AWS, Google Cloud, and Azure have become highly valued in the industry and can meaningfully strengthen a resume, especially for infrastructure, DevOps, and cloud architecture roles. Security certifications such as CISSP, CEH, or CompTIA Security+ are similarly impactful for security engineering positions. For software engineering, certifications are generally less important than demonstrated project experience, though Kubernetes certifications (CKA, CKAD) and specific vendor certifications can be differentiators.\n"
"\n"
"Continuous learning signals are increasingly important as technology evolves rapidly. If you have completed significant online courses, bootcamps, or specialized training programs, include them in an education or professional development section. Contributions to open-source projects, conference presentations, technical blog posts, and published papers also demonstrate ongoing intellectual engagement with your field. These elements are especially valuable when you are pivoting to a new technology area, as they show proactive investment in skills development beyond your current role."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-fundamentals.ts
msgid ""
"The education section of your resume provides information about your academic background. How prominently you feature this section depends on where you are in your career. For recent graduates, education may be the strongest section on the resume and should appear near the top, potentially even before work experience. For experienced professionals, education is typically listed after work experience and kept brief.\n"
"\n"
"For each educational entry, include the degree name, the name of the institution, its location, and your graduation date (or expected graduation date if you are still enrolled). If you graduated with honors, such as magna cum laude or summa cum laude, include that distinction. You may also list your GPA if it is 3.5 or higher and you are within the first few years of your career; beyond that point, GPA becomes less relevant and can be omitted.\n"
"\n"
"Include relevant coursework, academic projects, thesis topics, or research experience if they directly relate to the position you are applying for. This is especially important for recent graduates who may lack extensive professional experience. A computer science graduate applying for a data science role might list courses in machine learning, statistical modeling, and database systems to demonstrate subject-matter knowledge.\n"
"\n"
"Professional certifications, licenses, and continuing education credentials can be listed either within the education section or in a separate \"Certifications\" section. Industry-recognized certifications such as PMP, CPA, AWS Solutions Architect, or Google Analytics carry significant weight and should be prominently displayed. Include the certifying body and the date obtained; if the certification requires renewal, note that it is current.\n"
"\n"
"If you attended college but did not complete your degree, you can still list the institution and the credits or coursework completed. Format it as \"Coursework in Business Administration, University of Michigan, 2018-2020\" rather than leaving a misleading impression of degree completion. Honesty in this section is paramount, as educational credentials are among the most commonly verified items in background checks."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-formats.ts
msgid ""
"The effectiveness of a functional resume hinges on how well you organize and present your skills. Begin by carefully analyzing the job descriptions for positions you are targeting. Identify the three to five most important skill areas or competencies that employers are seeking. These will become the headings for your skill categories. Common categories include project management, technical expertise, leadership, communication, data analysis, customer relations, and strategic planning.\n"
"\n"
"Under each skill category, list three to five specific accomplishments or examples that demonstrate your proficiency. These should be drawn from any relevant experience, including formal employment, freelance work, volunteer activities, academic projects, or personal initiatives. The key is to treat each bullet point as evidence of your capability, not just a description of a task you performed.\n"
"\n"
"When writing your skill bullets, follow the same principles of strong resume writing that apply to any format. Use action verbs, quantify results when possible, and focus on outcomes rather than duties. For example, under a \"Project Management\" heading, you might write \"coordinated cross-functional team of 8 members to deliver a product launch 2 weeks ahead of schedule, resulting in a 15% increase in first-quarter revenue.\"\n"
"\n"
"Be strategic about the order in which you present your skill categories. Place the most relevant category first, as this is what the reader will see immediately. If the job emphasizes leadership and you have strong leadership examples, make that your first category. If it emphasizes technical skills, lead with those instead.\n"
"\n"
"Include a brief work history section below your skills section. Even though the functional format de-emphasizes chronological history, omitting it entirely can raise red flags with recruiters. List your positions with job title, company name, and dates of employment. You do not need to include bullet points or detailed descriptions for each role since your skills section already covers your accomplishments.\n"
"\n"
"Finally, ensure that your skills section tells a coherent story. Each category should build upon the last, creating a comprehensive picture of your professional identity. Avoid listing skills that are too broad or too vague, such as \"good communication\" or \"team player.\" Instead, provide specific, evidence-backed demonstrations of those abilities that give the reader confidence in your qualifications."
msgstr ""

