#: src/data/wiki/categories/interview-preparation.ts
msgid ""
"The environment you choose for your phone interview can significantly impact your performance and the impression you make on the interviewer. Select a quiet, private space where you will not be interrupted by roommates, family members, pets, or background noise. If you are at home, inform others about the call time and close doors and windows to minimize distractions. Test your phone reception in the chosen location beforehand to ensure you have a strong, reliable signal throughout the call.\n"
"\n"
"Have all your preparation materials laid out in front of you before the call begins. This includes your resume, the job description, your research notes about the company, a list of questions you want to ask, and a notepad and pen for taking notes. One of the advantages of a phone interview is that you can reference these materials without the interviewer seeing, so use this to your advantage. However, avoid shuffling papers loudly or sounding like you are reading directly from a script.\n"
"\n"
"Charge your phone fully and disable call waiting, notifications, and any other alerts that could interrupt the conversation. If possible, use a landline or a headset with a microphone for clearer audio quality. Background apps, text messages, and social media notifications can be surprisingly loud and distracting, both for you and for the interviewer. Test your audio by calling a friend a few minutes before the interview to confirm everything sounds clear.\n"
"\n"
"Consider standing during the phone interview, as this naturally projects more energy and confidence in your voice. Many voice coaches recommend standing and even walking slowly because it improves breathing and vocal projection. Have a glass of water nearby in case your throat gets dry, but avoid eating or chewing gum during the call. These may seem like small details, but they collectively contribute to a professional and polished phone presence."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"The experience section is where career changers face their greatest challenge. Every bullet point must be carefully crafted to emphasize the aspects of your previous roles that align with your target career.\n"
"\n"
"Start by conducting a thorough audit of your past responsibilities and achievements. For each item, ask yourself: \"How does this relate to the job I want?\" You will likely find that many of your accomplishments have direct parallels in your target industry. A teacher who managed a classroom of 30 students while meeting individualized education goals has project management skills. A sales representative who analyzed market trends and customer behavior has data analysis capabilities.\n"
"\n"
"Use action verbs that are common in your target industry. If you are transitioning into technology, words like \"implemented,\" \"optimized,\" \"analyzed,\" and \"automated\" carry more weight than \"taught,\" \"counseled,\" or \"supervised,\" even if the underlying skills are the same. This linguistic alignment helps hiring managers mentally place you in the new role.\n"
"\n"
"Quantify your achievements wherever possible. Numbers transcend industry boundaries. Whether you increased revenue by 25 percent, reduced processing time by 40 percent, or managed a budget of half a million dollars, these metrics demonstrate impact in a universal language that every hiring manager understands.\n"
"\n"
"Remove or minimize details that anchor you too firmly in your previous industry. If you spent ten years in healthcare administration and are transitioning to tech project management, you do not need to list every healthcare-specific certification or procedure you are familiar with. Keep the focus on the transferable elements: leadership, process improvement, stakeholder management, and data-driven decision making."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/industry-guides.ts
msgid ""
"The experience section of a trade resume must convey hands-on competence through precise descriptions of the work you have performed. Vague descriptions like performed maintenance duties or assisted with installations tell an employer nothing useful. Instead, specify the types of systems, equipment, and materials you worked with, the scale of the projects, and the outcomes of your work.\n"
"\n"
"For each position, describe your responsibilities using industry-specific terminology that demonstrates insider knowledge. An HVAC technician might write that they installed and serviced commercial rooftop units ranging from five to twenty-five tons, performed refrigerant recovery and charging using EPA-compliant procedures, and diagnosed control system faults using multimeters and manifold gauges. This level of detail immediately tells a hiring manager that you know the work, the tools, and the regulatory requirements.\n"
"\n"
"Include the types of environments you have worked in, as this information helps employers assess your fit for their specific operations. Trades work varies enormously between residential and commercial settings, new construction and retrofit projects, industrial plants and institutional facilities. An electrician who has wired high-rise commercial buildings brings different experience than one who has focused on residential remodeling. Neither is inherently superior, but the distinction matters for matching candidates to positions.\n"
"\n"
"Quantify your experience wherever possible. Mention the number of units you have installed or serviced, the square footage of projects you have completed, the value of contracts you have worked on, or the size of the teams you have led. If you have experience managing helpers or apprentices, note the team size and your supervisory responsibilities. Trades employers value candidates who can not only perform the technical work but also organize and direct the efforts of others, especially for foreman and lead technician positions."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/industry-guides.ts
msgid ""
"The experience section of an engineering resume should tell the story of your technical contributions and their real-world impact. Each role entry should go beyond listing technologies used and instead describe the problems you solved, the architectural decisions you made, and the outcomes your work produced. This narrative approach is what separates memorable resumes from forgettable ones.\n"
"\n"
"Structure each bullet point using the Context-Action-Result framework. Start with a brief description of the challenge or context, explain the technical approach you took, and conclude with a measurable outcome. For example, instead of writing that you worked on the payment processing system, write that you redesigned the payment processing pipeline to handle asynchronous webhook reconciliation, reducing failed transaction rates by thirty-seven percent and recovering an estimated two hundred thousand dollars in annual revenue.\n"
"\n"
"When describing projects, be specific about your individual contribution, especially in team environments. Engineering managers know that large systems are built by teams, and they want to understand your specific role. Use phrases like led the design of, implemented the core logic for, or architected the migration strategy for to clearly delineate your contributions from the broader team effort. This specificity builds trust and helps interviewers prepare more targeted technical questions.\n"
"\n"
"Include a mix of different types of contributions to demonstrate versatility. Highlight new feature development to show your ability to build from scratch, optimization work to demonstrate performance engineering skills, debugging and incident response to show your diagnostic abilities, and mentoring or code review contributions to demonstrate leadership. Senior engineers should also mention architectural decisions, technical strategy contributions, and cross-team collaboration, as these responsibilities are expected at higher levels and differentiate you from mid-level candidates.\n"
"\n"
"For open-source contributions, side projects, or hackathon wins, include a dedicated projects section if these are significant and relevant to your target role. Provide a one-sentence description of the project, your role, the technologies used, and any notable outcomes such as GitHub stars, downloads, production usage, or recognition. This section is particularly valuable for engineers transitioning to new technology domains or those with shorter professional experience who need to demonstrate broader technical capability."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/ats-optimization.ts
msgid ""
"The file format you choose for your resume is the very first factor that determines whether an ATS can read it. Submitting your resume in the wrong format can result in the system being completely unable to parse your content, effectively making your application invisible to recruiters.\n"
"\n"
"The safest and most universally compatible format is a .docx file (Microsoft Word). Nearly every ATS on the market can parse Word documents reliably. The .docx format preserves your formatting while maintaining a text layer that the parser can read. If a job posting does not specify a preferred format, .docx is almost always the best choice.\n"
"\n"
"PDF files are the second most common option, and most modern ATS platforms can parse them effectively. However, there is an important distinction between different types of PDFs. A PDF generated from a word processor or a resume builder tool typically contains selectable text that an ATS can read. In contrast, a PDF created by scanning a printed document is essentially an image file with no extractable text, and an ATS cannot parse it at all. If you submit a PDF, ensure it is a text-based PDF by trying to select and copy text from it.\n"
"\n"
"Plain text files (.txt) are guaranteed to be ATS-compatible because they contain no formatting that could confuse a parser. However, the lack of formatting makes plain text resumes visually unappealing to human readers. Use this format only as a last resort or when specifically requested.\n"
"\n"
"Avoid submitting resumes in formats like .pages (Apple Pages), .odt (OpenDocument), or image formats like .jpg or .png. These formats are either unsupported by many ATS platforms or cannot be parsed for text content. Similarly, avoid using Google Docs links unless the application specifically accepts them, as many ATS platforms cannot access or parse linked documents."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"The final two critical mistakes relate to the end of your letter and the beginning of the application process, respectively. Both are easy to fix once you are aware of them, but failing to address them can render even an otherwise excellent cover letter ineffective.\n"
"\n"
"Ending your cover letter without a call to action is like building a compelling sales presentation and then forgetting to ask for the sale. Many candidates close with a passive \"Thank you for your consideration\" and stop, leaving the next steps entirely in the hiring manager's hands. A strong call to action gently moves the process forward: \"I would welcome the opportunity to discuss how my experience can contribute to your team's goals and am available for a conversation at your earliest convenience.\" This signals confidence and makes it easy for the hiring manager to take the next step.\n"
"\n"
"Failing to follow application instructions is perhaps the most avoidable mistake on this list, yet it disqualifies more candidates than you might expect. When a job posting asks for specific information in your cover letter -- such as salary requirements, availability date, references, or answers to screening questions -- you must include that information. Ignoring these instructions suggests that you either did not read the posting carefully or chose to disregard it, neither of which reflects well on you.\n"
"\n"
"Similarly, if the posting specifies the file format (PDF versus Word), the subject line for email submissions, or the method of delivery (portal versus email), follow those instructions exactly. Some employers use specific instructions as a screening test to filter out candidates who do not pay attention to details. Compliance with instructions costs you nothing and eliminates an easy reason for rejection.\n"
"\n"
"Read the job posting at least twice before finalizing your application: once for the role requirements that inform your letter's content, and once for the application logistics that determine how you submit it. This simple habit prevents one of the most frustrating outcomes in the job search -- being eliminated not for lack of qualifications, but for lack of attention to detail."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/industry-guides.ts
msgid ""
"The finance industry is not monolithic, and a single resume will not effectively serve applications across different subsectors. Understanding the distinct expectations of each career path and tailoring your resume accordingly is essential for competitive positioning. The differences between what an investment bank, a Big Four firm, a hedge fund, a corporate treasury, and a fintech startup look for in a resume are significant enough to warrant maintaining separate versions.\n"
"\n"
"Investment banking and private equity resumes should emphasize deal experience, financial modeling skills, and the ability to work under intense time pressure. Lead with your experience on live transactions, including deal types, industry sectors, and transaction sizes. Highlight your modeling capabilities and any proprietary analysis you contributed to pitch books or investment committee presentations. For private equity, include portfolio company involvement and value creation initiatives. The tone should convey analytical rigor, attention to detail, and the capacity for sustained high performance.\n"
"\n"
"Public accounting resumes for Big Four and mid-tier firms should emphasize client diversity, engagement complexity, and progressive responsibility. List the industries you have served, the types of engagements you have led or participated in, and the professional standards you have applied. If you have experience with SEC reporting, SOX compliance, or international financial reporting standards, these specializations significantly strengthen your candidacy. For tax professionals, reference the complexity of the returns you have prepared and the advisory projects you have contributed to.\n"
"\n"
"Corporate finance and FP&A resumes should highlight your impact on business decision-making. Emphasize your experience with budgeting and forecasting, strategic analysis, capital allocation recommendations, and cross-functional collaboration. Corporate finance employers want to see that you can translate financial data into business insights and communicate those insights to non-financial stakeholders. If you have presented analysis to senior leadership or influenced significant business decisions through your financial work, these accomplishments are highly compelling and should be featured prominently.\n"
"\n"
"For fintech, financial technology, and data-driven finance roles, blend traditional finance credentials with technology skills. These employers want candidates who understand both the financial domain and the technical tools that are transforming it. Highlight your experience with data analysis, automation, machine learning applications in finance, or any involvement in technology transformation projects within financial organizations. The ability to bridge the gap between finance and technology is increasingly rare and valuable."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-fundamentals.ts
msgid ""
"The first and most important decision in writing your resume is selecting the right format. Your choice of format determines how your information is organized and which aspects of your background receive the most emphasis. The three main formats are chronological, functional, and combination, and the best choice depends on your career history, the role you are targeting, and any potential red flags you need to address.\n"
"\n"
"The chronological format is the gold standard and should be your default choice unless you have a compelling reason to use another format. It lists your work experience in reverse chronological order, making it easy for recruiters to trace your career progression. This format works best when you have a consistent work history in a relevant field and want to showcase career growth. Approximately 90 percent of resumes follow this format, and it is the most compatible with Applicant Tracking Systems.\n"
"\n"
"If you are changing careers, re-entering the workforce after a long gap, or have a non-traditional background, the combination format may serve you better. It allows you to lead with a robust skills section before presenting your chronological work history, giving you the opportunity to frame your experience in terms of transferable competencies rather than job titles.\n"
"\n"
"Before choosing a format, research common resume practices in your target industry. Some fields, such as creative industries, may welcome unconventional formats, while more traditional sectors like finance, law, or government typically expect a straightforward chronological resume. When in doubt, keep it conventional. The goal is to make the recruiter's job easy, not to showcase your design skills unless you are applying for a design role."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"The first paragraph of your cover letter is the most important section of your entire application. Hiring managers typically make a snap judgment within the first few sentences about whether your letter is worth reading in full. A compelling opening hooks the reader immediately, while a bland or generic introduction causes them to lose interest and move on to the next candidate's application.\n"
"\n"
"Think of your opening paragraph as the headline of a newspaper article. Just as a great headline draws readers into the story, a strong cover letter opening draws the hiring manager into your professional narrative. You have roughly 5 to 10 seconds to convince the reader that your letter contains something worth their time. This is not hyperbole -- with hundreds of applications to review, hiring managers develop a rapid-fire filtering process that eliminates generic letters almost instantly.\n"
"\n"
"The opening paragraph should accomplish three things simultaneously: identify the role you are applying for, establish your most compelling qualification or connection to the company, and create enough intrigue that the reader feels compelled to continue. This is a tall order for just two or three sentences, which is precisely why crafting the perfect opening requires more time and thought than any other part of the letter.\n"
"\n"
"Common advice to \"just be yourself\" in your opening is well-intentioned but incomplete. You need to be the most strategic, articulate version of yourself. The opening paragraph is where you deploy your strongest weapon -- whether that is a remarkable achievement, a personal connection to the company's mission, or a unique perspective that no other candidate can offer."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"The format of your cover letter is as important as its content. A well-formatted cover letter communicates professionalism, attention to detail, and respect for the reader's time before they even begin reading your words. Conversely, a poorly formatted letter -- with inconsistent spacing, walls of text, or unconventional layouts -- can create a negative first impression that undermines even the strongest qualifications.\n"
"\n"
"The standard professional cover letter follows a business letter format that has evolved for the digital age. While traditional business letters required strict formatting rules for physical mail, modern cover letters are typically submitted as PDF attachments or pasted into online application systems. Regardless of the submission method, the fundamental structure remains consistent: a header with contact information, a greeting, body paragraphs, and a professional closing.\n"
"\n"
"Understanding this format is not about rigidly following outdated conventions. It is about leveraging a structure that hiring managers expect and can process quickly. When your cover letter follows the expected format, the reader can focus on your message rather than being distracted by an unusual layout. This is especially important when your letter passes through applicant tracking systems, which may struggle to parse non-standard formatting.\n"
"\n"
"The key principle underlying all cover letter formatting decisions is readability. Every choice you make about margins, fonts, spacing, and structure should serve the goal of making your content as easy to read and absorb as possible. A hiring manager reviewing dozens or hundreds of applications will naturally gravitate toward letters that are clean, organized, and visually inviting."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/ats-optimization.ts
msgid ""
"The format of your resume refers to how you organize and present your work history, skills, and qualifications. There are three primary resume formats: reverse chronological, functional, and combination. Each has different implications for ATS compatibility, and choosing the right one can significantly impact how well your resume is parsed and scored.\n"
"\n"
"The reverse chronological format is the gold standard for ATS compatibility. This format lists your work experience starting with your most recent position and working backward in time. Each role includes a job title, company name, employment dates, and bullet points describing your responsibilities and achievements. ATS platforms are specifically designed to parse this format because it follows the most common and expected resume structure. The clear timeline makes it easy for the system to extract your job history, calculate your years of experience, and match your most recent qualifications against the job requirements.\n"
"\n"
"The functional format, which groups your experience by skill categories rather than by employer, is the least ATS-friendly option. Functional resumes de-emphasize dates and employer names in favor of skill clusters, which makes it difficult for the ATS to determine where and when you gained specific experience. Many ATS parsers struggle with this format because the expected job title, company, and dates structure is absent or buried. Recruiters are also often suspicious of functional resumes because they can hide employment gaps.\n"
"\n"
"The combination or hybrid format blends elements of both chronological and functional approaches. It typically includes a prominent skills section followed by a reverse chronological work history. This format can be ATS-compatible if the work history section follows standard chronological conventions. The skills section at the top provides an opportunity for keyword-rich content while the chronological history satisfies the parser's structural expectations. If you choose a combination format, ensure that your work experience section is detailed enough for the ATS to parse each role individually.\n"
"\n"
"For the vast majority of job seekers, the reverse chronological format is the recommended choice. It works reliably across all ATS platforms, satisfies recruiter expectations, and provides the clearest picture of your professional trajectory. Use a combination format only if you have a strong strategic reason, such as a career change that requires prominent skill emphasis."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"The format you choose for your career change resume can make or break your application. The three main formats, chronological, functional, and combination, each have distinct advantages and disadvantages for career changers.\n"
"\n"
"A functional resume organizes your experience by skill category rather than by employer and date. This format allows you to group transferable skills together, making it easier for hiring managers to see your relevant qualifications. However, many recruiters are suspicious of functional resumes because they can obscure employment gaps or a lack of direct experience.\n"
"\n"
"The combination format, also called a hybrid resume, is generally the best choice for career changers. It starts with a strong skills section or professional summary that highlights your transferable qualifications, followed by a brief chronological work history. This gives you the best of both worlds: the ability to lead with relevance while still providing the employment timeline that recruiters expect.\n"
"\n"
"Regardless of format, your resume should be tailored to each specific job posting. Use the job description as a blueprint, identifying the key skills and qualifications mentioned, and mirror that language in your resume. Applicant tracking systems (ATS) are programmed to look for specific keywords, so aligning your language with the job description is essential for getting past the initial automated screening.\n"
"\n"
"Consider adding a career summary statement at the top of your resume that explicitly addresses your transition. A statement like \"Marketing professional with 8 years of data-driven campaign management transitioning to product management\" immediately tells the reader who you are, what you bring, and where you are headed."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-formats.ts
msgid ""
"The functional resume format is specifically designed for job seekers whose strengths are not best represented through a traditional chronological listing of positions. Career changers are among the primary beneficiaries of this format. If you are transitioning from marketing to user experience design, for example, leading with a chronological list of marketing positions would not immediately signal your suitability for a UX role. A functional resume allows you to organize your transferable skills, such as user research, data analysis, and stakeholder communication, under categories that directly align with UX requirements.\n"
"\n"
"Professionals returning to the workforce after an extended absence also benefit significantly from the functional format. Whether the gap was due to raising children, dealing with a health issue, pursuing education, or caring for a family member, a functional resume shifts attention away from the timeline and toward your capabilities. It allows you to present yourself as a qualified candidate whose skills remain current and relevant, even if your most recent employment was several years ago.\n"
"\n"
"Recent graduates and early-career professionals who have limited formal work experience but strong academic projects, internships, volunteer work, and relevant skills can use a functional resume to present a compelling case. By grouping experiences from different contexts under skill categories, you can demonstrate depth of knowledge that might not be apparent from a brief list of part-time jobs or internships.\n"
"\n"
"Veterans transitioning to civilian careers often find the functional format useful as well. Military experience involves highly specialized terminology and organizational structures that do not always translate directly to civilian job descriptions. A functional resume allows veterans to frame their military skills in language that civilian employers understand, focusing on leadership, logistics, crisis management, and other transferable competencies.\n"
"\n"
"Freelancers and consultants with diverse project histories may also consider this format. Rather than listing dozens of short-term engagements that could make your resume look fragmented, you can group your project work under skill categories that demonstrate breadth and depth of expertise. This approach presents a more cohesive picture of your professional capabilities."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-formats.ts
msgid ""
"The functional resume format offers distinct advantages for the right candidates. Its primary strength is the ability to direct attention toward your skills and accomplishments rather than your employment timeline. This is invaluable for career changers, as it allows you to reframe your experience in terms that are relevant to your target role. Instead of hoping the recruiter will see the connection between your previous career and the new one, you make that connection explicitly through your skill categories.\n"
"\n"
"Another advantage is the ability to consolidate experience from multiple sources. If your relevant skills were developed across several different jobs, volunteer positions, and personal projects, a functional resume lets you present them as a unified body of expertise. This can be particularly powerful for candidates who have diverse backgrounds that contribute to a rich, multifaceted skill set.\n"
"\n"
"The functional format also provides flexibility in highlighting your most impressive accomplishments regardless of when they occurred. If your most significant achievement happened in a role you held eight years ago, you can feature it prominently under the relevant skill category without it being buried deep in your work history.\n"
"\n"
"However, the functional resume format carries significant disadvantages that you must weigh carefully. The most critical drawback is that many recruiters and hiring managers are suspicious of functional resumes. They may assume you are using the format to hide gaps, lack of experience, or frequent job changes. Some recruiters have openly stated that they discard functional resumes without reading them because they find the format evasive.\n"
"\n"
"Applicant tracking systems also struggle with functional resumes. Most ATS software is designed to parse chronological formats, matching job titles and companies with dates and then extracting skills and keywords. The non-standard structure of a functional resume can confuse these systems, potentially causing your resume to be filtered out before a human ever sees it. In an era where the majority of large employers use ATS, this is a serious concern.\n"
"\n"
"The functional format can also make it difficult for readers to understand the context of your accomplishments. When a bullet point mentions that you \"increased customer retention by 30%,\" the reader naturally wants to know where, when, and in what role this happened. Without that context, the achievement may feel unanchored and less credible. This is why many career experts now recommend the combination format as a more effective alternative to the purely functional resume."
msgstr ""

#: src/routes/dashboard/tools/-components/elevator-pitch-components.tsx
msgid "The Golden Rule"
msgstr "La règle d'or"

#: src/routes/dashboard/resumes/-components/experience-optimizer-components.tsx
msgid "The golden rule: every bullet point should start with a powerful action verb and include at least one quantifiable metric. Transform your responsibilities into achievements using the CAR method (Challenge, Action, Result)."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-sections.ts
msgid ""
"The GPA question is one of the most debated topics in resume writing. The general guideline is to include your GPA if it is strong (3.5 or above on a 4.0 scale, or 14/20 and above in the French system) and you graduated within the last three to five years. Beyond that window, your work experience should speak for itself.\n"
"\n"
"If your overall GPA is not impressive but your major GPA is, list the major GPA instead and label it clearly: \"Major GPA: 3.7/4.0.\" This is a common and accepted practice that highlights your strength in your field of study.\n"
"\n"
"For international students or graduates applying to positions in different countries, include the grading scale for clarity. Writing \"16/20 (French system)\" or \"First Class Honours (UK system)\" helps recruiters who may not be familiar with your country's grading conventions.\n"
"\n"
"Some industries care more about GPA than others. Finance, consulting, and certain engineering firms often use GPA as a screening threshold, especially for entry-level roles. Technology companies, creative fields, and many other industries place less emphasis on grades and more on portfolio work, projects, and practical experience.\n"
"\n"
"If your GPA is below 3.0 or the equivalent, it is generally better to omit it. Leaving it off is not suspicious; many experienced professionals do not include it. However, if a job application specifically asks for your GPA, always provide it honestly."
msgstr ""

