#: src/data/wiki/categories/job-search-strategies.ts
msgid ""
"The job board ecosystem has evolved dramatically beyond the simple listing sites of the early internet. Today's landscape includes general aggregators like Indeed and LinkedIn, company-specific career pages, niche industry boards, recruiter platforms, and AI-powered matching services. Understanding the strengths and limitations of each platform type is essential for an efficient job search.\n"
"\n"
"General job boards like Indeed and LinkedIn Jobs aggregate millions of postings and offer the broadest reach. Their scale makes them useful for surveying the market and understanding demand patterns, but their size also means more competition per listing. A single posting on LinkedIn can receive hundreds of applications within the first 24 hours, making it essential to apply early and differentiate your application.\n"
"\n"
"Niche job boards focused on specific industries, roles, or demographics often produce higher quality matches with less competition. Platforms like Stack Overflow Jobs for developers, Mediabistro for media professionals, Dice for technology roles, or Idealist for nonprofit positions attract candidates and employers who are specifically committed to those sectors, resulting in more relevant opportunities and more engaged hiring managers.\n"
"\n"
"Company career pages are often the most direct and effective channel for applying. Many companies post positions on their own career pages days or weeks before they appear on aggregator sites, and internal applicant tracking systems often prioritize direct applications over those forwarded from third-party boards. Identifying your target companies and checking their career pages regularly ensures you see opportunities first and apply through the preferred channel."
msgstr ""

