#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid "The most common cover letter mistake is sending a generic, untailored letter to multiple employers. Hiring managers can immediately detect a mass-produced cover letter, and it signals a lack of genuine interest in their specific role and company. Customizing each cover letter to reference the specific company, role, and how your experience aligns with their needs dramatically increases your chances of getting an interview."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"The most common mistake job seekers make is writing a generic cover letter and sending it to dozens of employers. Effective cover letters are tailored to each specific opportunity, and that process begins with thorough research. Before you write a single word, you should understand the company's mission, recent achievements, challenges in their industry, and the specific requirements of the role you are targeting.\n"
"\n"
"Start by reading the job description carefully -- not just once, but multiple times. Highlight the key skills, qualifications, and responsibilities mentioned. Pay attention to the language the company uses, as mirroring their terminology in your cover letter demonstrates alignment and familiarity with their culture. If the posting emphasizes \"collaborative problem-solving,\" use that exact phrase when describing your relevant experience.\n"
"\n"
"Next, explore the company's website, social media channels, recent press releases, and any available employee reviews. Look for information about their values, current projects, and strategic direction. This research will help you craft specific, meaningful connections between your background and what the company needs. For example, instead of writing \"I am excited about your company,\" you could write \"I was inspired by your recent initiative to expand renewable energy access in underserved communities, and I believe my experience in sustainable project management would contribute directly to that mission.\"\n"
"\n"
"Finally, if possible, identify the hiring manager by name. A cover letter addressed to a specific person feels more personal and shows initiative. LinkedIn is an excellent resource for identifying the right contact. If you cannot find a name, \"Dear Hiring Manager\" or \"Dear [Department] Team\" are acceptable alternatives that avoid the outdated and overly formal \"To Whom It May Concern.\""
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid "The most commonly sought transferable skills include communication (written and verbal), leadership and team management, problem-solving and analytical thinking, project management, adaptability, time management, and interpersonal skills. Technical skills like data analysis, digital literacy, and proficiency with productivity software are also highly valued across industries."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-sections.ts
msgid ""
"The most critical rule of reference etiquette is simple: always ask permission before listing someone as a reference. Listing someone without their knowledge is disrespectful and can result in a caught-off-guard reference who provides a lukewarm or confused recommendation.\n"
"\n"
"Timing matters. Contact your references before you start actively applying, not after you have already submitted applications. Give them a week or two of notice before they might receive a call. If a specific company is about to check references, send a heads-up message with the company name, the role, and any specific points you would like them to address.\n"
"\n"
"After the process is complete, whether you got the job or not, thank your references. A brief thank-you email expressing appreciation for their time and support maintains the relationship and makes them willing to help again in the future. If you landed the role, share the good news. People who helped you succeed enjoy knowing they made a difference.\n"
"\n"
"Common mistakes include listing too many references from the same company, which can appear as if you have a limited professional network. Another error is including a reference you have not contacted in years, who may not remember you well enough to provide a strong recommendation. Outdated contact information is another frequent problem. Verify phone numbers and email addresses before submitting your reference page.\n"
"\n"
"Never list a reference who you suspect might give a negative or lukewarm recommendation. If you are unsure how someone would speak about you, it is better to choose a different reference. You can diplomatically gauge someone's willingness by asking, \"Would you be comfortable serving as a strong reference for me?\" The emphasis on \"strong\" gives them an out if they have reservations."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"The most damaging cover letter mistake is also the most common: writing one generic letter and sending it to every employer with minimal changes. Hiring managers can spot a mass-produced cover letter from the first sentence, and it immediately signals that you are not genuinely interested in their specific company or role. In a competitive job market, generic applications are essentially a guarantee of rejection.\n"
"\n"
"A generic cover letter typically contains vague, interchangeable language like \"I am excited about the opportunity to work for your company\" or \"I believe my skills make me a great fit for this role.\" These statements could apply to literally any position at any company, which means they add zero persuasive value. Contrast this with a tailored statement: \"Your company's recent expansion into renewable energy infrastructure aligns perfectly with the six years I spent developing project management frameworks for large-scale solar installations.\" The difference in impact is dramatic.\n"
"\n"
"The fix is straightforward but requires discipline: customize every cover letter for every application. This does not mean rewriting from scratch each time. Create a strong base template with your core qualifications and storytelling, then modify the opening, company-specific references, and closing for each application. Budget 20 to 30 minutes per customization. This investment of time dramatically increases your callback rate compared to sending dozens of identical letters.\n"
"\n"
"Research each company before writing. Reference specific projects, values, recent news, or challenges that demonstrate you have done your homework. Mention the exact job title and department. If possible, address the letter to a specific person by name. These details transform your letter from a mass mailing into a personal communication that commands attention."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/remote-work.ts
msgid ""
"The most damaging mistake is treating a remote job application like any other application. Submitting a generic resume that does not address remote work capabilities signals to the employer that you have not thought carefully about what remote work requires or that you are mass-applying without genuine interest in the specific opportunity.\n"
"\n"
"Avoid emphasizing the lifestyle benefits of remote work rather than the professional value you bring. Hiring managers do not want to hear that you are attracted to remote work because you want to avoid commuting or work in your pajamas. They want to know that you are attracted to remote work because you are more productive, more focused, and more effective when you have the autonomy and environment that remote work provides.\n"
"\n"
"Do not overlook the importance of communication skills on a remote resume. In an office, you can rely on casual conversations, body language, and proximity to convey information. Remotely, almost everything passes through written communication. If your resume contains typos, unclear language, or poor formatting, the employer will wonder how your written communication will hold up in daily Slack messages, documentation, and email updates.\n"
"\n"
"Avoid listing every digital tool you have ever touched. Instead, focus on tools you have used substantially and can discuss knowledgeably in an interview. Listing 30 tools suggests you are padding your resume, while listing 8 to 12 highly relevant tools that you have used in meaningful ways demonstrates focused expertise.\n"
"\n"
"Do not ignore the ATS optimization that is especially critical for remote positions. Because remote roles attract more applicants, companies rely more heavily on automated screening. Ensure your resume uses standard formatting that ATS systems can parse, includes the exact keywords from the job posting, and avoids graphics, tables, or unusual layouts that may confuse automated screening tools."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-sections.ts
msgid ""
"The most effective approach for many candidates is a hybrid statement that combines the best elements of both formats. It opens with a brief professional identity (like a summary) and closes with a targeted goal (like an objective), creating a complete narrative in a compact format.\n"
"\n"
"The formula is: professional identity plus key qualification plus target direction. For example: \"Data scientist with three years of experience in predictive modeling and natural language processing, seeking to apply advanced analytics expertise to improve patient outcomes at a healthcare innovation company.\"\n"
"\n"
"This hybrid approach works because it satisfies both the employer's need to know what you can do and the candidate's need to signal intentional career direction. It is especially effective for career pivoters who have relevant skills but not directly relevant titles, and for candidates targeting specific industries or company types.\n"
"\n"
"To write an effective hybrid statement, start with your strongest professional identifier (your current or most relevant job title and years of experience), add one or two high-value qualifications or achievements, and end with a specific statement about what you want to do next and where. The specificity of the goal portion is what differentiates it from a generic objective.\n"
"\n"
"Avoid making the statement too long. Two to three sentences is the sweet spot. If it runs longer, you have crossed into summary territory and should commit to that format instead. The hybrid works precisely because it is concise and decisive."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"The most effective cover letter openings fall into several proven categories, each suited to different situations and candidates. Understanding these strategies gives you a toolkit to craft the perfect opening for any application.\n"
"\n"
"The Achievement Lead opens with a specific, quantifiable accomplishment that directly relates to the role. For example: \"In my three years as a product manager at TechVentures, I led the launch of a platform feature that grew our user base by 340,000 active users and increased quarterly revenue by $4.2 million.\" This approach works best when you have a standout achievement that clearly demonstrates your ability to deliver results in the target role.\n"
"\n"
"The Passion Connection Lead demonstrates genuine enthusiasm for the company's specific mission or work. For example: \"When I read about [Company]'s breakthrough in personalized cancer treatment protocols, I immediately recognized the intersection of data science and healthcare that has driven my career for the past seven years.\" This approach is particularly effective when the company has a compelling mission or has recently made headlines for impressive work.\n"
"\n"
"The Mutual Contact Lead leverages a professional referral to establish immediate credibility. For example: \"After speaking with Sarah Chen on your engineering team about the challenges your platform faces at scale, I was excited to see the opening for a Senior Backend Engineer.\" Referral candidates are statistically far more likely to be hired, and mentioning a mutual contact in your opening immediately elevates your letter above cold applications.\n"
"\n"
"The Bold Statement Lead opens with a confident, thought-provoking claim that positions you as an expert. For example: \"The biggest challenge facing fintech companies today is not technology -- it is trust. I have spent eight years building the kind of trust that turns cautious first-time users into loyal customers, and I want to bring that expertise to [Company].\" This approach works well for senior roles and candidates who want to demonstrate industry thought leadership.\n"
"\n"
"The Story Lead draws the reader in with a brief, relevant anecdote. For example: \"Last month, I automated a reporting process that had consumed 12 hours of my team's time every week. As I watched my colleagues redirect that time toward creative problem-solving, I was reminded why I became a process engineer.\" This narrative approach creates an emotional connection and makes your letter stand out from the more formulaic entries in the applicant pool."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/salary-negotiation.ts
msgid ""
"The most effective long-term negotiation approach is collaborative rather than adversarial. In collaborative negotiation, you and the employer work together to find a compensation package that satisfies both parties. This approach preserves the relationship, creates goodwill, and often results in better outcomes than hardball tactics.\n"
"\n"
"Start by expressing genuine enthusiasm for the role and the company. Make it clear that you want to find a way to make this work. Then frame your salary expectations in terms of mutual benefit. Instead of saying \"I need more money,\" try \"I want to make sure the compensation reflects the value I will bring to this role, especially given my experience with X and Y which directly address your team's priorities.\"\n"
"\n"
"Ask questions to understand the employer's constraints. Budgets are real, and salary bands exist for legitimate organizational reasons. By understanding where there is flexibility and where there is not, you can redirect the conversation toward components where movement is possible. If the base salary is capped by a company-wide pay band, there may be room in the signing bonus, equity grant, vacation days, or start date.\n"
"\n"
"Present options rather than demands. Instead of a single counter-number, offer two or three packages that would be acceptable. For example, Package A might feature a higher base salary, while Package B pairs a moderate base increase with a signing bonus, and Package C adds more equity. This gives the employer the feeling of choice and control while ensuring that every option meets your needs.\n"
"\n"
"Use the phrase \"Is there any flexibility on...\" rather than \"I want more.\" This invites collaboration rather than triggering defensiveness. The employer becomes a problem-solving partner rather than an opponent, which dramatically increases the likelihood of a positive outcome for both sides."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-sections.ts
msgid ""
"The most frequent mistake is writing a generic summary that could apply to anyone. If you can swap your name with a stranger's and the summary still makes sense, it is too vague. Tailor every summary to the specific job description by mirroring the language and priorities listed in the posting.\n"
"\n"
"Another common error is making the summary too long. Anything beyond five sentences starts to feel like a cover letter pasted into the wrong section. Recruiters scan, they do not read in the initial pass. Keep it tight and scannable.\n"
"\n"
"Avoid first-person pronouns. Instead of writing \"I am an experienced project manager,\" write \"Experienced project manager with...\" This is a widely accepted resume convention that keeps the tone professional and concise.\n"
"\n"
"Listing soft skills without evidence is another pitfall. Saying you have \"excellent communication skills\" means nothing without context. Instead, demonstrate it: \"Presented quarterly earnings analyses to C-suite stakeholders across four international offices.\" The achievement implies the skill far more convincingly than the claim.\n"
"\n"
"Finally, do not include information that belongs elsewhere, such as your full employment history or a list of every technology you have ever used. The summary is a highlight reel, not an exhaustive inventory."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"The most important step in creating a civilian resume is systematically replacing military jargon with language that any hiring manager can understand. This does not mean dumbing down your experience; it means expressing it in the vocabulary of the civilian workplace.\n"
"\n"
"Start with your job titles. Military occupational specialties and ranks should be translated into their civilian equivalents. An Army E-7 Platoon Sergeant becomes a \"Senior Operations Manager.\" A Navy Operations Specialist becomes a \"Data Analyst and Communications Coordinator.\" An Air Force Logistics Readiness Officer becomes a \"Supply Chain and Logistics Manager.\" Research civilian job titles that correspond to your military role and use those on your resume.\n"
"\n"
"Replace acronyms and military-specific terms throughout your resume. \"MOS\" becomes \"job specialty.\" \"PCS\" becomes \"relocation.\" \"SITREP\" becomes \"status report.\" \"AOR\" becomes \"assigned region\" or \"operational area.\" If you are unsure whether a term is military-specific, err on the side of translating it. A simple test is to ask a civilian friend or family member to read your resume and flag any terms they do not understand.\n"
"\n"
"When describing your achievements, focus on the business equivalents of military operations. Training exercises become \"professional development programs.\" Force protection becomes \"security management.\" Mission planning becomes \"strategic project planning.\" The underlying competencies are the same; only the terminology changes.\n"
"\n"
"Use online military-to-civilian translation tools as a starting point, but do not rely on them exclusively. These tools can suggest civilian equivalents for common military terms, but they cannot capture the nuance of your specific experience. Review and refine every translation to ensure it accurately represents your accomplishments."
msgstr ""

