msgstr "Le bon moment peut faire toute la différence dans une négociation"

#: src/data/wiki/categories/ats-optimization.ts
msgid ""
"The section headings you use in your resume play a critical role in how an ATS categorizes your information. ATS parsers are programmed to recognize standard heading names and associate the content beneath them with specific data fields. Using unconventional or creative headings can prevent the system from correctly classifying your experience, skills, or education.\n"
"\n"
"Use these standard section headings that virtually every ATS recognizes: \"Professional Summary\" or \"Summary,\" \"Work Experience\" or \"Experience,\" \"Education,\" \"Skills,\" \"Certifications,\" and \"Awards.\" These labels are universally understood by ATS parsing engines and will reliably route your content to the correct fields in the system's database.\n"
"\n"
"Avoid creative alternatives like \"Where I've Made an Impact\" instead of \"Experience,\" \"My Toolbox\" instead of \"Skills,\" or \"Academic Journey\" instead of \"Education.\" While these headings might appeal to human readers, the ATS may fail to categorize the content beneath them, resulting in missing or misplaced information in your candidate profile.\n"
"\n"
"If you need to include additional sections beyond the standard set, use descriptive but conventional labels. \"Volunteer Experience,\" \"Professional Development,\" \"Publications,\" \"Languages,\" and \"Projects\" are all widely recognized by ATS platforms. If you are unsure whether a heading will be recognized, err on the side of simplicity and use the most straightforward label possible.\n"
"\n"
"Capitalization and formatting of your headings should be consistent throughout the document. Whether you choose title case, all capitals, or bold formatting, apply the same style to every section heading. This consistency helps the ATS parser identify section boundaries reliably and ensures that all your content is properly categorized."
msgstr ""

#: src/routes/dashboard/resumes/-components/compare-components.tsx
msgid "The selected resumes are identical or no changes were detected."
msgstr "Les CV sélectionnés sont identiques ou aucune modification n'a été détectée."

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-sections.ts
msgid ""
"The short answer for most situations is no. In the modern job market, references are not typically included directly on the resume. The standard practice is to prepare a separate reference page that you provide when requested, usually during the later stages of the interview process.\n"
"\n"
"There are several reasons for this convention. First, resume space is precious. Every line occupied by reference names and phone numbers is a line that could be used to showcase your skills, achievements, or experience. For a one-page resume, this trade-off is particularly costly.\n"
"\n"
"Second, including references without being asked can put your references in an awkward position. They may receive unexpected calls before you have had a chance to brief them about the specific role or company. References perform best when they are prepared and know what to emphasize, which requires advance notice from you.\n"
"\n"
"Third, privacy concerns have made employers more cautious about how they handle personal contact information. Many organizations have moved to formal reference check processes that occur at defined stages, making unsolicited reference information premature.\n"
"\n"
"However, there are exceptions. Some job postings specifically ask for references to be included with the application. In these cases, follow the instructions exactly. Government positions, academic applications, and some nonprofit roles may require references upfront. When the posting asks for them, provide them."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"The sign-off is the final visual element of your cover letter, and choosing the right one matters more than many candidates realize. Your sign-off should match the tone of your letter and the culture of the organization while maintaining professionalism.\n"
"\n"
"The safest and most universally appropriate sign-offs are \"Sincerely,\" \"Best regards,\" and \"Kind regards.\" These work for any industry, any level of formality, and any type of role. If your letter has maintained a slightly more conversational tone, \"Best,\" or \"Warm regards,\" are acceptable alternatives that feel approachable without sacrificing professionalism.\n"
"\n"
"Avoid overly casual sign-offs like \"Cheers,\" \"Thanks,\" or \"Talk soon\" unless you have a pre-existing relationship with the recipient or the company culture is extremely informal (and you are certain of this based on research, not assumption). On the other end of the spectrum, avoid antiquated formal sign-offs like \"Respectfully yours,\" \"Your humble servant,\" or \"I remain, your obedient applicant\" which feel comically outdated.\n"
"\n"
"After your sign-off, include your full name. If submitting a PDF or physical letter, consider adding a digital signature above your typed name for a polished touch. Below your name, you may include your phone number and email address again for convenience, especially if submitting through a portal where your header information might be separated from the letter body.\n"
"\n"
"Ensure there is appropriate spacing between your closing paragraph and your sign-off (one blank line) and between your sign-off and your name. If your letter will be printed, leave enough space (three to four lines) between the sign-off and your typed name for a physical signature. These formatting details may seem minor, but they contribute to the overall impression of professionalism and care."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/salary-negotiation.ts
msgid ""
"The single biggest mistake is not negotiating at all. Studies show that not negotiating your starting salary can cost you over one million dollars in lost earnings over a 30-year career, due to the compounding effect of percentage-based raises and bonuses built on a lower base. Even a modest negotiation that increases your starting salary by five percent compounds dramatically over time.\n"
"\n"
"Another costly mistake is accepting the first offer immediately out of gratitude or relief. Even if the offer seems generous, taking time to evaluate it is expected and professional. Instant acceptance can actually make the employer wonder if they offered too much, while a thoughtful pause followed by a reasonable negotiation signals that you value yourself appropriately.\n"
"\n"
"Avoid making ultimatums unless you are truly prepared to walk away. Saying \"I need X or I cannot accept\" backs both you and the employer into a corner. If the employer cannot meet that number, you have eliminated all room for creative solutions. Instead, use ranges and express flexibility on how the total compensation is structured.\n"
"\n"
"Do not bring personal financial needs into the negotiation. Statements like \"I need this salary because my mortgage is X\" or \"I have student loans to pay\" are not persuasive to employers. The negotiation should be based on your market value and the value you bring to the organization, not your personal expenses.\n"
"\n"
"Never lie about competing offers or your current salary. This is both unethical and risky, as companies increasingly verify compensation history and communicate with each other. If caught in a lie, you will likely lose the offer entirely and damage your professional reputation. If you have a legitimate competing offer, it is perfectly appropriate to mention it, but fabricating one is a career-ending risk.\n"
"\n"
"Finally, do not negotiate by email when a phone or video call is possible. Tone is lost in written communication, and what you intend as collaborative can read as demanding. Voice conversations allow for real-time rapport building, and the back-and-forth flow of a live conversation creates momentum toward agreement that email exchanges cannot match."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/interview-preparation.ts
msgid ""
"The Situation component sets the stage for your story by providing the context the interviewer needs to understand what was happening. Describe the specific circumstances you were in, including where you were working, what project or challenge you were involved in, and any relevant background information. Be specific enough to paint a clear picture, but concise enough to avoid spending more than fifteen to twenty percent of your total answer on this section. The interviewer needs context, not an exhaustive history.\n"
"\n"
"When selecting a situation to describe, choose one that is relevant to the question being asked and, ideally, relevant to the role you are interviewing for. If the interviewer asks about a time you demonstrated leadership, do not choose an example from a context completely unrelated to the professional world unless it is truly exceptional. Professional examples carry more weight because they demonstrate you can apply the skill in a work environment similar to the one you are seeking to join.\n"
"\n"
"The Task component defines your specific responsibility within the situation. This is where you clarify what was expected of you and what challenge or goal you needed to address. The distinction between Situation and Task is subtle but important: the Situation is the broader context, while the Task is your personal assignment or objective within that context. For example, the Situation might be that your team was behind on a critical project deadline, and your Task was to reorganize the workflow to get the project back on track.\n"
"\n"
"Be clear about why the task mattered and what was at stake. This creates urgency in your narrative and helps the interviewer understand the significance of your contribution. If the task involved measurable goals, mention them here so the interviewer can later appreciate the results you achieved. A well-defined task also demonstrates that you understood your responsibilities and took them seriously."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/industry-guides.ts
msgid ""
"The skills section of a hospitality resume should balance service-oriented competencies with operational and technical skills. Hospitality-specific skills include guest relations, conflict resolution, event coordination, food and beverage management, menu development, revenue management, banquet operations, and quality assurance. Include only the skills that you can substantiate with examples from your experience, as hospitality interviews frequently involve scenario-based questions that test claimed competencies.\n"
"\n"
"Language skills are uniquely valuable in hospitality. Hotels, restaurants, and tourism operations serve international clientele, and the ability to communicate in multiple languages directly impacts guest satisfaction and operational efficiency. List every language you speak along with your proficiency level, such as fluent, conversational, or basic. If you have used your language skills in a professional hospitality context, mention this in your experience descriptions. Bilingual and multilingual candidates often receive preference in hiring, especially in international hotel brands and tourist-heavy markets.\n"
"\n"
"Technology proficiency is increasingly important as hospitality operations become more digitized. List the property management systems you have used, such as Opera PMS, Maestro, or RoomKey. Include point-of-sale systems like Micros, Toast, or Aloha. Mention any experience with revenue management platforms like IDeaS or Duetto, customer relationship management systems, online reputation management tools, or event management software. For candidates targeting corporate or multi-property roles, experience with business intelligence tools, workforce management systems, and enterprise reporting platforms is particularly relevant.\n"
"\n"
"Food safety and alcohol service certifications should be included for any candidate in a food and beverage role. ServSafe Food Handler and Manager certifications, TIPS or ServSafe Alcohol certifications, and any state-specific food handler permits are often prerequisites for employment and should be listed in your certifications section. If you hold additional hospitality certifications such as the Certified Hospitality Professional (CHP) or Certified Hotel Administrator (CHA) from the American Hotel and Lodging Educational Institute, these credentials strengthen your resume significantly and demonstrate commitment to professional development."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-sections.ts
msgid ""
"The skills section serves a dual purpose on your resume. First, it acts as a quick-reference index that allows recruiters to verify at a glance whether you possess the specific competencies they need. Second, it is one of the most heavily scanned sections by applicant tracking systems, which match your listed skills against the keywords in the job posting.\n"
"\n"
"Studies show that recruiters spend an average of 7.4 seconds on an initial resume scan. During that brief window, the skills section is one of three areas that consistently receives attention, alongside the job titles and company names in your experience section. A well-organized skills section can be the difference between landing in the \"yes\" pile and being passed over.\n"
"\n"
"For ATS purposes, the skills section is indispensable. Many ATS platforms assign a match score based heavily on keyword presence, and the skills section is the most natural place to include these keywords. Even if your experience bullets mention the same skills in context, having them listed explicitly in a dedicated section ensures the ATS parser can identify them without ambiguity.\n"
"\n"
"This section is also where you can showcase breadth. While your experience section demonstrates depth in specific roles, the skills section can highlight the full range of tools, technologies, languages, and methodologies you command. This is particularly valuable in fast-moving industries where tool familiarity can be a hiring differentiator."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-sections.ts
msgid ""
"The skills you list should be driven by the job description, not by everything you have ever learned. Start by reading the posting carefully and highlighting every skill, tool, technology, and competency mentioned. These are the keywords the ATS and recruiter will be looking for.\n"
"\n"
"Cross-reference that list with your own abilities. Only include skills you can genuinely demonstrate or discuss in an interview. Listing a programming language you used once in a tutorial five years ago will backfire when you are asked to whiteboard a solution. Be honest about your proficiency levels.\n"
"\n"
"Prioritize skills by relevance. The first skills a recruiter sees should be the ones most critical to the role. If you are applying for a front-end developer position and the posting emphasizes React, TypeScript, and responsive design, those should appear before your Python or SQL skills, even if you are more proficient in the latter.\n"
"\n"
"Research the industry standard tools. If every posting in your target field mentions a specific platform or certification, include it if you have it. Industry-specific tools often serve as gatekeepers: lacking them can disqualify you immediately, while having them signals you can contribute from day one.\n"
"\n"
"Remove outdated or irrelevant skills. Listing Microsoft Word proficiency in 2026 takes up space that could be used for meaningful skills. Similarly, technologies that are no longer widely used (unless the posting specifically mentions them) can make your resume feel dated. Keep your skills list current and forward-looking."
msgstr ""

