#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"The stigma around career gaps has diminished significantly in recent years, but it has not disappeared entirely. Hiring managers are increasingly understanding of gaps caused by caregiving responsibilities, health issues, education, or personal development. However, how you address the gap on your resume still matters.\n"
"\n"
"The global pandemic permanently changed how employers view career gaps. Millions of workers experienced involuntary gaps during 2020 and 2021, and many more chose to step away for caregiving or personal reasons in the years that followed. As a result, a gap on your resume is no longer the red flag it once was. Employers now focus more on what you can do than on whether your work history is perfectly continuous.\n"
"\n"
"That said, the way you frame your gap can make a significant difference in how your resume is received. A gap that appears unintentional or unexplained still raises questions. Addressing it proactively and positively shows self-awareness and confidence, two qualities that employers value in any candidate.\n"
"\n"
"The most important thing to understand is that a career gap does not erase your skills or diminish your professional value. Skills developed over years of work do not expire during a period of absence. Your challenge is to demonstrate that you remained engaged, continued to grow, and are ready to contribute from day one."
msgstr ""

