#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"Transferable skills are abilities and competencies that you develop in one context and can apply effectively in a completely different setting. Unlike technical or industry-specific skills, transferable skills transcend job titles, departments, and entire industries. They are the foundation upon which career changes are built.\n"
"\n"
"These skills fall into several broad categories: communication, leadership, analytical thinking, problem-solving, project management, interpersonal relations, and organizational abilities. Every professional develops these skills to some degree, regardless of their industry. A nurse who coordinates patient care across multiple departments is exercising the same project management skills as a software development team lead.\n"
"\n"
"Transferable skills matter because they represent your core professional capabilities, the underlying competencies that make you effective regardless of the specific domain. Employers increasingly recognize that industry-specific knowledge can be taught relatively quickly, but skills like critical thinking, emotional intelligence, and strategic planning take years to develop.\n"
"\n"
"In the context of a career change, transferable skills are your primary currency. They bridge the gap between what you have done and what you want to do. When a hiring manager looks at your resume, your transferable skills are the evidence that you can succeed in a new environment even without direct industry experience."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/industry-guides.ts
msgid ""
"Transferable skills are the foundation of every strong entry-level resume. These are competencies that apply across industries and roles, and they are exactly what employers evaluate when candidates lack direct professional experience. The most valued transferable skills include communication, problem-solving, teamwork, time management, adaptability, analytical thinking, and leadership. Your resume must provide concrete evidence of these skills through specific examples rather than simply listing them as abstract qualities.\n"
"\n"
"To identify your transferable skills, review every significant activity you have been involved in during the past three to five years. For each activity, ask yourself what challenges you faced, what skills you used to address them, and what the outcome was. A retail job demonstrates customer service, conflict resolution, and the ability to work under pressure. A research assistant position shows analytical thinking, attention to detail, and the ability to work independently. Leading a student organization demonstrates project management, communication, and leadership.\n"
"\n"
"When writing about transferable skills on your resume, always anchor them to specific situations and outcomes. Instead of listing communication skills in a generic skills section, describe how you presented research findings to a panel of faculty members and received the highest grade in your cohort. Instead of claiming you are a strong team player, explain how you coordinated a team of six volunteers to organize an event that attracted three hundred attendees and raised five thousand dollars for a local charity. These specific, grounded examples are infinitely more persuasive than self-assessed qualities.\n"
"\n"
"Create a skills section that blends transferable skills with any technical or domain-specific skills you have developed. If you are targeting technology roles, list programming languages, tools, and platforms alongside your transferable competencies. For business roles, include software proficiency, data analysis capabilities, and any industry-specific knowledge. This blended approach demonstrates both your foundational capabilities and your readiness to contribute in the specific domain you are targeting."
msgstr ""

