#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"Transitioning from freelance or contract work to a full-time position presents a distinct set of resume challenges that differ from other career transitions. Freelancers must convince employers that they can thrive within an organizational structure after years of independence, while simultaneously presenting a diverse portfolio of projects as a coherent career narrative.\n"
"\n"
"The primary concern hiring managers have about freelance candidates is commitment. They worry that someone accustomed to the freedom and variety of freelancing will become restless in a full-time role and leave within months. Your resume needs to counter this perception by demonstrating stability, teamwork, and long-term engagement with clients or projects.\n"
"\n"
"Another challenge is the fragmented nature of freelance work. Where a traditional employee might list three or four positions over a decade, a freelancer could have worked with dozens or even hundreds of clients. Listing every project would create a resume that is pages long and impossible to parse. Instead, you need a strategy for consolidating your freelance experience into a clear, compelling narrative.\n"
"\n"
"Freelancers also face the challenge of proving their skills without the implicit endorsement of a well-known employer's name. When a resume says \"Software Engineer at Google,\" the brand carries weight. When it says \"Freelance Software Engineer,\" the candidate must work harder to establish credibility. Your resume must use other signals, such as notable clients, impressive metrics, and relevant certifications, to build that trust."
msgstr ""

