#: src/data/wiki/categories/networking-linkedin.ts
msgid ""
"Understanding how recruiters use LinkedIn Recruiter, the premium tool that most corporate talent acquisition teams and staffing agencies use, can fundamentally change how you optimize your profile. Recruiters build Boolean search strings using keywords, titles, locations, companies, and skills to generate candidate lists. They then review profiles in a condensed card format that shows your headline, current title, location, and a few lines of your summary.\n"
"\n"
"To appear in recruiter searches, your profile must contain the exact keywords they are searching for. Study ten to fifteen job descriptions for your target role and identify the most frequently used terms. These terms should appear in your headline, summary, experience section, and skills list. If every senior product manager job description mentions \"roadmap,\" \"stakeholder management,\" and \"data-driven decision making,\" those phrases need to be present throughout your profile.\n"
"\n"
"Your current title and headline carry the most weight in LinkedIn Recruiter search results. If your actual job title is unusual or company-specific, consider adding a more recognizable equivalent. For example, if your official title is \"Growth Hacker III,\" you might format your headline as \"Growth Hacker III (Senior Growth Marketing Manager)\" to capture searches for both the specific and the conventional title.\n"
"\n"
"Recruiter behavior patterns reveal additional optimization opportunities. Most recruiters focus on the first page of search results, meaning your profile's ranking matters enormously. Profile completeness, recent activity, mutual connections with the recruiter, and a track record of responding to InMail messages all influence your ranking. Keep your profile 100 percent complete, engage regularly with content on the platform, and respond promptly to any recruiter messages, even if the opportunity is not a fit.\n"
"\n"
"When a recruiter reaches out with an opportunity that interests you, respond within 24 hours. Express enthusiasm, ask clarifying questions about the role, and confirm your interest in a screening call. If the role is not a fit, respond politely and indicate what types of opportunities you are seeking. Maintaining positive recruiter relationships benefits you in the long term, as recruiters remember professionals who are responsive and courteous."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-formats.ts
msgid ""
"Understanding how the combination resume compares to the chronological and functional formats will help you determine whether it is the right choice for your situation. The chronological resume excels in simplicity and familiarity. It is the format that most recruiters expect and that most ATS software is built to parse. However, it forces you to present your experience in a rigid timeline that may not showcase your strongest qualifications first. If your most relevant skills were developed across multiple roles or outside of formal employment, the chronological format can work against you.\n"
"\n"
"The functional resume solves the problem of leading with skills, but it introduces new challenges. By de-emphasizing your work history, it can raise suspicion among hiring managers who want to understand the context of your accomplishments. It also performs poorly with applicant tracking systems, which rely on being able to associate specific achievements with specific employers and time periods. Many career experts have moved away from recommending purely functional resumes for these reasons.\n"
"\n"
"The combination resume occupies the strategic middle ground. It gives you the flexibility to lead with your most relevant skills and accomplishments, satisfying the reader's immediate question of \"can this person do the job?\" It then follows with a chronological work history that provides the context and credibility that functional resumes lack. This dual structure also performs better with ATS software than a functional resume because it still includes the standard chronological elements that these systems are designed to parse.\n"
"\n"
"However, the combination format has its own challenges. It is inherently longer than a chronological resume because it includes both a detailed skills section and a work history section. This means you need to be disciplined about conciseness to avoid exceeding two pages. There is also a risk of redundancy: if the same accomplishment appears in both your skills section and your work experience section, it can feel repetitive and suggest that you are padding your resume.\n"
"\n"
"The combination format also requires more effort to tailor for each application. Because you are organizing skills into categories and matching them to job requirements, you need to restructure your skills section for different positions. This is more work than simply adjusting a few bullet points in a chronological resume, but the payoff in terms of relevance and impact is significant.\n"
"\n"
"Ultimately, the best format depends on your unique circumstances. If you have a strong, linear career progression, the chronological format remains the safest bet. If you are changing careers or re-entering the workforce, the combination format offers the most balanced approach. Reserve the functional format for situations where your work history would actively work against you and you are confident the recipient will not penalize you for using a non-standard format."
msgstr ""

