#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-sections.ts
msgid ""
"Understanding what reference checkers typically ask can help you prepare both yourself and your references. Most reference calls follow a standard set of questions, though the specifics vary by company and role.\n"
"\n"
"Common questions include: \"How do you know the candidate and for how long?\" \"What were their primary responsibilities?\" \"How would you describe their work quality?\" \"Can you give an example of a challenge they handled well?\" \"What are their greatest professional strengths?\" \"Are there areas where they could improve?\" \"Would you rehire them?\" and \"Is there anything else you think we should know?\"\n"
"\n"
"The \"Would you rehire?\" question is often considered the most telling. A hesitant or qualified answer here can raise red flags, while an enthusiastic \"Absolutely\" is a strong endorsement. Make sure your references would answer this question positively.\n"
"\n"
"Some employers use structured reference check forms with rating scales, asking references to score the candidate on specific competencies like reliability, communication, leadership, and technical ability. Others conduct informal conversational calls. Either way, references who can provide specific examples and anecdotes are far more persuasive than those who offer only general praise.\n"
"\n"
"Help your references help you by sharing the job description and highlighting the two or three qualities you most want them to emphasize. If the role requires strong project management skills and your reference supervised you on a complex project, remind them of that project and suggest they share that example during the call. This coaching is expected and appropriate, as long as you are not asking them to exaggerate or fabricate."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-formats.ts
msgid ""
"Understanding which industries and roles welcome creative resume formats will help you make an informed decision about whether to invest in a visual design. The creative and design industries are the most obvious fit. Graphic designers, web designers, UX/UI designers, illustrators, photographers, and art directors are all expected to demonstrate visual literacy in their application materials. In these fields, a standard black-and-white resume can feel like a missed opportunity to showcase your abilities.\n"
"\n"
"Marketing and advertising professionals also benefit from creative resume formats. These industries value innovation, brand awareness, and the ability to capture attention. A resume that demonstrates these skills through its design sends a powerful message about your creative capabilities. Digital marketers, brand managers, content strategists, and social media managers can all leverage creative formatting to differentiate themselves.\n"
"\n"
"The entertainment and media industries, including film, television, music, fashion, and publishing, tend to be receptive to creative resumes. These fields operate in highly visual environments where aesthetics matter. A resume that reflects an understanding of visual storytelling and contemporary design trends can set you apart from candidates who submit conventional formats.\n"
"\n"
"Startups and tech companies, particularly those with a strong emphasis on design and user experience, often appreciate creative resumes. Companies like Apple, Airbnb, and Spotify have design-forward cultures where visual communication is valued across all departments, not just the design team. If the company's own brand aesthetic is bold and creative, a resume that reflects similar sensibilities can demonstrate cultural alignment.\n"
"\n"
"Architecture and interior design firms expect candidates to present materials that reflect their design capabilities. A resume that demonstrates strong typography, thoughtful use of space, and visual hierarchy shows the same skills that will be applied to architectural or design projects.\n"
"\n"
"It is important to note that even within creative industries, the level of creativity that is appropriate varies by role and seniority. A junior graphic designer might use bold colors and unconventional layouts to demonstrate range, while a creative director might opt for a more refined, sophisticated design that reflects leadership and strategic thinking. Always consider the specific expectations of the role and company culture before deciding how creative to make your resume."
msgstr ""

