#: src/data/wiki/categories/salary-negotiation.ts
msgid ""
"When it comes time to negotiate, present your research strategically rather than dumping raw data on the hiring manager. Lead with the market context by saying something like \"Based on my research across multiple compensation databases, the market range for this role in this geography is between X and Y.\" This establishes that your expectations are grounded in data, not arbitrary demands.\n"
"\n"
"Reference specific sources when appropriate, but avoid making the conversation feel like a courtroom presentation. A natural framing might be \"Glassdoor and LinkedIn both show the median for this role at X, and industry salary surveys from Robert Half confirm that range.\" This demonstrates thorough preparation without being confrontational.\n"
"\n"
"Use your research to reframe the conversation from what you want to what the market supports. Instead of \"I need X dollars,\" try \"The market data suggests that someone with my experience and skills in this role typically earns between X and Y. Given my specific background in Z, I believe a salary at the higher end of that range is appropriate.\" This positions your ask as a fair market rate rather than a personal demand.\n"
"\n"
"Be prepared for the employer to present their own data. Companies often use compensation surveys from Mercer, Willis Towers Watson, or Radford that may show different ranges. Rather than dismissing their data, acknowledge it and discuss why the ranges might differ. Factors like company size, total compensation structure, and survey methodology can explain legitimate differences. The goal is a collaborative conversation about fair market value, not a data battle.\n"
"\n"
"If you have competing offers or recent salary data from your own career, these can be powerful negotiation tools. An offer letter from another company with a specific number is the strongest possible evidence of your market value. Even without a competing offer, your current compensation serves as a data point that any new offer should meaningfully exceed to justify a career move."
msgstr ""

#: src/routes/builder/$resumeId/-components/header.tsx
#: src/routes/dashboard/resumes/-components/menus/context-menu.tsx
#: src/routes/dashboard/resumes/-components/menus/dropdown-menu.tsx
msgid "When locked, the resume cannot be updated or deleted."
msgstr "Lorsqu'il est verrouillé, le CV ne peut être ni modifié ni supprimé."

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-sections.ts
msgid ""
"When references are requested, you should have a polished reference page ready to provide. This document should match the visual style of your resume (same header, fonts, and formatting) to create a cohesive application package.\n"
"\n"
"Each reference entry should include the person's full name, their current job title, the company they work for, their phone number, their email address, and your professional relationship to them (for example, \"Former direct supervisor at ABC Company\" or \"Collaborated on cross-departmental projects for three years\").\n"
"\n"
"List three to five references, unless the employer specifies a different number. Three is the minimum that most employers find acceptable, while five provides a comfortable margin. Ordering them by relevance to the target role is more effective than listing them alphabetically or chronologically.\n"
"\n"
"Professional references should come from people who have directly observed your work performance. Former supervisors carry the most weight, followed by colleagues at the same level, clients you worked with closely, and mentors who know your professional capabilities. Avoid listing family members, personal friends, or anyone who cannot speak to your professional skills.\n"
"\n"
"Before listing anyone as a reference, always ask their permission. Explain the type of role you are pursuing and what skills or qualities you would like them to highlight. This preparation ensures they can provide a focused, enthusiastic reference rather than a vague or surprised one. Send them a copy of the job description and your resume so they have full context."
msgstr ""

