#: src/data/wiki/categories/salary-negotiation.ts
msgid ""
"When you have limited professional experience, you need to leverage different strengths in your negotiation. Instead of citing years of experience, focus on the specific skills, projects, and results from your academic career, internships, and extracurricular activities that are directly relevant to the role. A senior thesis project, a successful internship deliverable, or a leadership role in a student organization all demonstrate value.\n"
"\n"
"If you completed internships at the hiring company or its competitors, use this to your advantage. You already understand the company's culture, tools, and processes, which means a shorter ramp-up time and faster productivity. This reduced onboarding cost is a legitimate justification for a higher starting salary compared to a candidate who has never worked in the industry.\n"
"\n"
"Academic achievements like honors, scholarships, publications, or awards signal intellectual capability and drive that employers value. Relevant certifications, technical skills, or programming language proficiency can also justify higher compensation, especially in fields where specific technical skills are in high demand.\n"
"\n"
"Use the collaborative framing that works for all negotiations, but adapt it for your situation. Instead of \"I need more money,\" try \"I am very excited about this opportunity and want to start this relationship on the right foot. My research suggests that the market rate for this role is X, and given my internship experience at Company Y and my specialized skills in Z, I believe a salary at the midpoint of that range is appropriate.\"\n"
"\n"
"If the employer cannot move on base salary for entry-level positions, which is common at companies with rigid pay bands for new graduates, focus your negotiation on the signing bonus, start date flexibility, relocation assistance, professional development budget, or an early performance review with the possibility of a salary adjustment after six months."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-fundamentals.ts
msgid "When You Need a Resume"
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/salary-negotiation.ts
msgid ""
"When you resign from your current employer, there is a strong chance they will make a counter-offer to retain you. Research shows that 50 to 80 percent of employees who accept counter-offers from their current employer leave within 12 months anyway, making this one of the most statistically risky career decisions you can make.\n"
"\n"
"The primary reason counter-offers from current employers fail is that they address the symptom (compensation) but not the underlying reasons you decided to leave. If you are leaving because of limited growth opportunities, poor management, or cultural misalignment, a salary increase does not fix those problems. It simply adds a financial incentive to stay in a situation that was already not working.\n"
"\n"
"Additionally, accepting a counter-offer can damage trust with your current employer. You have revealed that you were actively looking to leave, and some managers will view you as a flight risk going forward. You may be passed over for future opportunities or find yourself first on the list if layoffs occur. The dynamics of the relationship change once resignation has been tendered, regardless of the counter-offer.\n"
"\n"
"If you do consider accepting a counter-offer, evaluate it against a comprehensive checklist: Does it address all the reasons you wanted to leave, not just compensation? Is it a permanent change or a temporary fix? Will your manager treat you the same way going forward? Are the promises in writing? Would you have received this increase without threatening to leave? If the answers to most of these questions are no, the data strongly suggests you should continue with your departure.\n"
"\n"
"If you decide to decline the counter-offer, do so graciously and professionally. Thank your employer for valuing your contributions enough to make the offer, explain that you have carefully considered it, and confirm that you have decided to proceed with your transition. Maintain the relationship because your industry network is small and you may cross paths with these colleagues again."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/ats-optimization.ts
msgid ""
"When you submit your resume through an online application portal, the ATS performs several operations before any human reviews your candidacy. The first step is parsing, which is the process of extracting structured data from your resume document. The parser reads your file and attempts to identify key fields such as your name, contact information, work history, education, skills, and certifications.\n"
"\n"
"Parsing technology works by recognizing patterns in document formatting. It looks for section headings like \"Experience,\" \"Education,\" and \"Skills\" to categorize information correctly. It identifies dates to determine employment timelines and reads bullet points to extract job responsibilities and achievements. The accuracy of this parsing depends heavily on how your resume is formatted. Clean, standard formatting parses well, while creative layouts with tables, text boxes, or unusual structures often confuse the parser and result in garbled or missing data.\n"
"\n"
"After parsing, the ATS scores or ranks your resume against the job description. This scoring mechanism compares the content of your resume to the requirements specified by the employer. The system looks for matching keywords, required qualifications, relevant job titles, and specific skills. Some ATS platforms use simple keyword matching, while more advanced systems employ natural language processing to understand synonyms, context, and related terms.\n"
"\n"
"The ranked results are then presented to the recruiter as a shortlist. Depending on the system and the employer's configuration, the ATS may automatically reject candidates who fall below a certain score threshold, or it may simply sort all applicants from highest to lowest match. In either case, your resume's compatibility with the ATS directly determines whether you advance in the hiring process.\n"
"\n"
"It is worth noting that ATS parsing is not perfect. Even the most sophisticated systems can misinterpret resume content if the document structure is unclear. This is precisely why understanding ATS mechanics matters: you can dramatically improve your chances by formatting your resume in a way that the system can accurately read and score."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"When your work experience does not directly align with your target career, your education, certifications, and side projects become powerful tools for demonstrating commitment and capability.\n"
"\n"
"If you have pursued any formal education related to your new field, whether it is a degree, a bootcamp, a certificate program, or even individual courses, place this section higher on your resume than you normally would. For career changers, relevant education can be more important than work experience in establishing credibility.\n"
"\n"
"Certifications are particularly valuable because they provide third-party validation of your skills. Many industries have recognized certification programs that can be completed in weeks or months. A Project Management Professional (PMP) certification, a Google Analytics certification, or an AWS cloud practitioner credential immediately signals to employers that you have invested time in building genuine expertise.\n"
"\n"
"Side projects and volunteer work deserve their own section on a career change resume. If you built a website for a nonprofit, managed social media for a friend's business, or contributed to an open-source project, these experiences demonstrate practical application of your new skills. They also show initiative and passion, qualities that employers value highly in career changers.\n"
"\n"
"Consider creating a portfolio or personal website that showcases your work in the new field. Include case studies, writing samples, design mockups, or code repositories, anything that provides tangible evidence of your abilities. Include the URL prominently on your resume so hiring managers can easily explore your work."
msgstr ""

