#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"While all transferable skills have value, some are more universally sought after than others. Understanding which skills carry the most weight can help you prioritize what to highlight on your resume.\n"
"\n"
"Communication skills consistently rank as the most valued transferable skill across virtually every industry. This includes written communication, verbal presentation, active listening, and the ability to tailor your message to different audiences. Whether you are writing code documentation, presenting a marketing strategy, or counseling a patient, effective communication is the common thread.\n"
"\n"
"Leadership and team management skills are highly transferable and increasingly important as organizations flatten their hierarchies. If you have experience motivating teams, delegating tasks, mentoring junior colleagues, or driving organizational change, these skills translate directly to almost any management or senior individual contributor role.\n"
"\n"
"Analytical and problem-solving skills are in high demand across every sector. The ability to gather data, identify patterns, evaluate options, and implement solutions is fundamental to roles in technology, consulting, finance, healthcare, and beyond. If you can demonstrate a track record of solving complex problems, employers will trust you to do the same in their industry.\n"
"\n"
"Project management skills, including planning, budgeting, timeline management, stakeholder communication, and risk assessment, are remarkably portable. Whether you managed construction projects, marketing campaigns, or clinical trials, the core discipline of moving a complex initiative from conception to completion is the same.\n"
"\n"
"Digital literacy has become a baseline transferable skill. Proficiency with common software tools, data management, social media, and basic technology troubleshooting is expected in nearly every modern workplace. If you have more advanced digital skills, such as data visualization, coding, or digital marketing, these become even more valuable differentiators."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/industry-guides.ts
msgid ""
"While guest satisfaction is foundational, hospitality is ultimately a business, and employers want team members who understand and contribute to the financial performance of the operation. Including revenue-related metrics and operational accomplishments on your resume demonstrates business acumen that sets you apart from candidates who focus solely on service delivery.\n"
"\n"
"For revenue-generating roles such as front desk agents, reservation specialists, catering managers, and restaurant servers, include metrics related to upselling performance, average check increases, occupancy rate contributions, and revenue per available room or per available seat. A front desk agent might note that they achieved the highest upsell conversion rate in the department at twenty-eight percent, generating an additional forty thousand dollars in room revenue during the quarter. A server might highlight an average per-cover spend that exceeded the restaurant average by fifteen percent through effective menu recommendations.\n"
"\n"
"Operational efficiency metrics are equally important, especially for back-of-house, housekeeping, engineering, and management positions. Include figures related to labor cost management, food cost control, inventory management, maintenance response times, room turnover rates, and event setup efficiency. If you implemented a process improvement that reduced costs or increased throughput, quantify the impact. For example, you might describe how you redesigned the housekeeping inspection workflow to reduce average room turnover time from thirty-two to twenty-four minutes while maintaining quality standards.\n"
"\n"
"For candidates targeting general management or area management positions, demonstrate your understanding of key performance indicators at the property level. Reference your experience managing profit and loss statements, capital budgets, and labor scheduling. Mention any experience with revenue management systems, property management systems, or enterprise reporting tools. These operational and financial competencies become increasingly important as you advance in hospitality and are essential for positions above the department head level."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/networking-linkedin.ts
msgid "While LinkedIn is essential, a personal website provides value that LinkedIn cannot. You own and control the content, design, and narrative completely. A personal website ranks well in search results for your name, can host a portfolio or blog that LinkedIn's format does not support well, and demonstrates technical initiative. For professionals in creative, technical, or executive roles, a personal website is particularly valuable. Even a simple one-page site significantly enhances your professional credibility."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-fundamentals.ts
msgid ""
"While missing information is problematic, sharing too much personal or irrelevant information on your resume can be equally damaging. Over-sharing can raise legal concerns, create bias, or simply waste space that could be used for more compelling professional content.\n"
"\n"
"Including personal information such as your age, date of birth, marital status, number of children, religious affiliation, political views, or Social Security number is inappropriate on resumes in the United States and many other countries. This information is not only irrelevant to your professional qualifications but can also expose both you and the employer to discrimination claims. Even if you feel this information works in your favor, its inclusion suggests unfamiliarity with professional norms.\n"
"\n"
"Listing hobbies and personal interests is generally unnecessary unless they are directly relevant to the position or demonstrate a skill the employer is seeking. If you are applying for a role at a sports media company, mentioning your marathon running or sports analytics hobby could be relevant. Otherwise, \"enjoys cooking, hiking, and reading\" adds nothing to your candidacy and takes up space that could highlight a professional achievement.\n"
"\n"
"Including references or the phrase \"References available upon request\" is an outdated practice that wastes a line of valuable resume space. Employers will ask for references when they need them, and they assume you can provide them. The same applies to salary history or salary expectations, which should never appear on a resume. These topics are appropriate for later in the interview process, not for the initial application document.\n"
"\n"
"Writing an excessively long resume when a shorter one would suffice is a form of over-sharing at the document level. Every additional page dilutes the impact of your best content. If your two-page resume has strong content on page one and filler content on page two, the recruiter's overall impression will be weaker than if you had submitted a single powerful page. Edit ruthlessly and remember that the best resumes are curated, not comprehensive."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/ats-optimization.ts
msgid "While not every company uses an ATS, the vast majority do. Over 98% of Fortune 500 companies use applicant tracking systems, and approximately 75% of all employers including small and mid-sized businesses use some form of ATS. If you are applying through an online portal or a job board, there is a very high probability that your resume will pass through an ATS before reaching a human recruiter."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"While transferable skills form the foundation of your career change, you may need to supplement them with industry-specific knowledge to be a competitive candidate. The good news is that targeted skill-building can be done relatively quickly and affordably.\n"
"\n"
"Online learning platforms like Coursera, edX, LinkedIn Learning, and Udemy offer courses in virtually every field. Completing relevant courses not only builds your knowledge but also gives you concrete credentials to list on your resume. Many courses offer certificates upon completion, which signal to employers that you have invested in learning about their industry.\n"
"\n"
"Hands-on experience is even more valuable than coursework. Look for volunteer opportunities, freelance projects, or internships that let you practice your new skills in a real-world context. Even small projects, such as building a website for a local nonprofit or analyzing data for a friend's business, provide practical experience you can reference on your resume.\n"
"\n"
"Networking within your target industry is itself a skill-building activity. Attend industry conferences, join professional associations, and participate in online communities. These interactions expose you to industry terminology, current trends, and common challenges, all of which help you speak the language of your new field with greater confidence and authenticity.\n"
"\n"
"Consider finding a mentor in your target industry who can guide your skill development and provide insider perspective on what employers truly value. A mentor can also review your resume and provide feedback from the hiring manager's point of view, helping you refine your presentation of both transferable and newly acquired skills."
msgstr ""

