#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-formats.ts
msgid ""
"Writing a chronological resume that stands out requires more than just listing your jobs in order. Start by tailoring your resume for each position you apply to. Study the job description carefully and identify the key skills, qualifications, and experiences the employer is seeking. Then, adjust your professional summary and the bullet points under each role to emphasize how your background aligns with those requirements.\n"
"\n"
"Use the STAR method (Situation, Task, Action, Result) to craft compelling bullet points for your work experience. Instead of describing what you were responsible for, describe what you accomplished and the impact it had. For example, rather than writing \"managed social media accounts,\" write \"developed and executed a social media strategy that increased engagement by 47% and grew the follower base from 5,000 to 23,000 within eight months.\"\n"
"\n"
"Quantify your achievements wherever possible. Numbers, percentages, dollar amounts, and timeframes add credibility and specificity to your claims. Hiring managers are drawn to measurable results because they provide concrete evidence of your capabilities. Even if your role was not directly tied to revenue, you can quantify improvements in efficiency, team productivity, error reduction, or customer satisfaction.\n"
"\n"
"Keep your formatting consistent and professional. Use the same font, font size, and spacing throughout the document. Align your dates to the right margin and your job titles and company names to the left. Use bold text sparingly to highlight job titles or section headings, and avoid excessive use of colors, graphics, or unusual layouts that might confuse ATS software.\n"
"\n"
"Limit your resume to one or two pages depending on your experience level. Entry-level candidates and those with fewer than ten years of experience should aim for a single page. Senior professionals with extensive experience may use two pages, but every line should add value. Remove outdated or irrelevant positions that do not contribute to your current career goals, and focus on the last 10 to 15 years of experience.\n"
"\n"
"Finally, proofread your resume meticulously. Spelling errors, grammatical mistakes, and formatting inconsistencies undermine your professionalism and attention to detail. Read your resume out loud, ask a trusted colleague to review it, and use professional tools to check for errors. A polished chronological resume demonstrates the same care and precision you will bring to the job."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"Writing a great opening paragraph is rarely a matter of inspiration striking on the first try. The most effective openings are the product of a deliberate, iterative process. Follow these steps to craft an opening that captures attention every time.\n"
"\n"
"Begin by identifying your single strongest selling point for this specific role. Review the job description and ask yourself: \"What is the one thing I can offer that would make a hiring manager stop and pay attention?\" This could be a remarkable achievement, a rare combination of skills, a personal connection to the company, or deep expertise in their most pressing challenge. This will be the centerpiece of your opening.\n"
"\n"
"Write three to five different versions of your opening paragraph, each using a different strategy from the approaches described above. Do not edit as you write -- just get different versions on paper. This exercise prevents you from anchoring to your first idea, which is rarely your best one.\n"
"\n"
"Step away from your drafts for at least an hour, then return with fresh eyes. Read each version aloud and notice which one creates the strongest emotional response. The best opening should make you feel something -- excitement, confidence, curiosity -- because if it does not move you, it certainly will not move a busy hiring manager.\n"
"\n"
"Refine your chosen draft by tightening the language, removing unnecessary words, and ensuring every sentence serves a clear purpose. Your final opening paragraph should be two to three sentences, totaling 40 to 60 words. This constraint forces precision and impact. Then, ask a trusted friend or colleague to read just the opening paragraph and tell you whether it makes them want to keep reading. Their honest reaction will tell you whether your opening is ready."
msgstr ""

