#: src/data/wiki/categories/interview-preparation.ts
msgid ""
"Your body language in a group interview setting is under even more scrutiny than in a one-on-one conversation because multiple observers are forming opinions simultaneously. Maintain an upright, open posture that conveys confidence and engagement. Avoid crossing your arms, slouching, or turning your body away from any of the interviewers or participants, as these signals can be interpreted as disinterest or defensiveness.\n"
"\n"
"When you are not the one speaking, your behavior still matters enormously. Active listening in a group setting means making eye contact with the person who is speaking, nodding appropriately, and maintaining engaged facial expressions. Interviewers often observe how candidates behave when they are not in the spotlight, as this reveals character traits like patience, respect, and genuine interest in others.\n"
"\n"
"In group activities with other candidates, be mindful of the physical space you occupy. Do not crowd other participants or physically position yourself in a way that excludes anyone from the conversation circle. If the group naturally clusters into smaller conversations, make sure no one is left out. These spatial dynamics may seem trivial, but they send powerful signals about your awareness of others and your collaborative instincts.\n"
"\n"
"Your energy level and enthusiasm should remain consistent throughout the group interview, which may last several hours. Fatigue and declining energy are natural but can negatively impact your performance in later exercises. Stay hydrated, maintain your posture, and remind yourself to smile and engage even when you feel tired. Candidates who sustain their energy and enthusiasm throughout a long group interview process demonstrate the stamina and commitment that employers find attractive."
msgstr ""

#: src/routes/dashboard/career/-components/branding-components.tsx
msgid "Your Brand Statement"
msgstr "Votre déclaration de marque personnelle"

#: src/routes/dashboard/tools/-components/ai-writer-panels.tsx
msgid "Your bullet points will appear here"
msgstr "Vos points clés apparaîtront ici"

#: src/data/wiki/categories/remote-work.ts
msgid ""
"Your camera setup is the single most impactful technical decision for a virtual interview. Position your camera at eye level, either by elevating your laptop on a stand or using an external webcam mounted on your monitor. A camera angled up from below creates an unflattering perspective that subconsciously undermines your presence. The camera should capture you from mid-chest up, providing enough of your body to convey natural gestures while keeping the focus on your face.\n"
"\n"
"Lighting makes or breaks your visual presentation. The ideal setup places a light source in front of you and slightly above, creating even illumination across your face without harsh shadows. Natural window light works well if the window is in front of you. Never sit with a window or bright light behind you, as this creates a silhouette effect that obscures your face. A simple ring light or desk lamp positioned correctly provides professional lighting that flatters your appearance.\n"
"\n"
"Audio quality is arguably more important than video quality because poor audio directly impedes communication. Use a dedicated microphone or quality headset rather than your laptop's built-in microphone, which picks up ambient noise and produces thin, distant sound. Test your audio in the actual environment where you will interview, at the same time of day, to identify potential noise issues like construction, traffic, or household sounds.\n"
"\n"
"Your internet connection must be reliable and fast enough for video conferencing. Test your connection speed at the time of day you will be interviewing. If your Wi-Fi is unstable, consider using a wired Ethernet connection. Have a mobile hotspot available as a backup in case your primary connection fails. Inform household members of your interview time so they can avoid bandwidth-heavy activities like streaming or large downloads.\n"
"\n"
"Familiarize yourself with the specific video conferencing platform the interviewer will use. Download and install the application in advance rather than relying on browser-based access, which is often less stable. Test your camera, microphone, and screen-sharing capabilities within the platform. Know how to mute, unmute, turn your camera on and off, and share your screen before the interview begins."
msgstr ""

