#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-sections.ts
msgid ""
"Your choice of references can reinforce or undermine your candidacy. The ideal reference is someone who can speak in specific, enthusiastic terms about your work performance, your character, and your potential for the role you are pursuing.\n"
"\n"
"Direct supervisors from your most recent and most relevant roles are the gold standard. They can speak authoritatively about your day-to-day performance, your accomplishments, and your professional growth. If you left a role on good terms, that supervisor should be your first call.\n"
"\n"
"If your relationship with a recent supervisor was strained, you have options. A supervisor from a previous role, a senior colleague who worked closely with you, or a department head who oversaw your projects can all serve as credible references. The key is that they observed your work firsthand and can provide specific examples.\n"
"\n"
"For career changers, include at least one reference from your target field if possible. This might be a professor from a certification program, a mentor in the new industry, or a supervisor from a volunteer or freelance project in the new domain. This reference can vouch for your transferable skills and your commitment to the transition.\n"
"\n"
"Diversity in your reference list is valuable. A mix of supervisors, peers, and clients demonstrates that you perform well across different relationships and dynamics. If every reference is a peer, a recruiter might wonder why no manager is willing to recommend you. Balance your list to cover multiple perspectives on your professional capabilities.\n"
"\n"
"Stay in touch with your references between job searches. A reference who has not heard from you in three years will provide a less detailed and less enthusiastic recommendation than one you have maintained a professional relationship with. Periodic check-ins, even brief ones, keep the relationship warm and the memories of your collaboration fresh."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"Your closing paragraph is your final opportunity to leave a strong impression, and many candidates underestimate its importance. A weak closing -- such as simply thanking the reader -- fails to capitalize on the momentum you have built throughout the letter. Instead, your conclusion should accomplish three things: reiterate your value proposition, express genuine enthusiasm for the opportunity, and include a clear call to action.\n"
"\n"
"Start by briefly summarizing why you are an excellent fit for the role. This does not mean repeating everything you have already said, but rather distilling your key message into one or two punchy sentences. For example: \"With a decade of experience driving product innovation at scale and a deep passion for user-centered design, I am confident I can help [Company Name] achieve its goal of becoming the market leader in accessible technology.\"\n"
"\n"
"Next, convey your excitement about the opportunity in a way that feels authentic. Avoid generic phrases like \"I would be thrilled to work for your company.\" Instead, reference something specific you learned during your research: \"The opportunity to contribute to your expansion into the European market is particularly exciting to me, given my experience launching products in three European countries.\"\n"
"\n"
"Finally, include a proactive call to action. Rather than passively waiting, signal your intent to follow up: \"I would welcome the opportunity to discuss how my experience aligns with your team's goals. I will follow up next week, but please do not hesitate to reach out at your convenience.\" This demonstrates initiative without being pushy.\n"
"\n"
"Close with a professional sign-off such as \"Sincerely,\" \"Best regards,\" or \"Respectfully,\" followed by your full name. If submitting a physical letter or a PDF, include a handwritten or digital signature for a polished touch."
msgstr ""

