#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-fundamentals.ts
msgid ""
"Your contact information section is the simplest part of your resume, but mistakes here can be costly. If a recruiter cannot easily find your phone number or email address, or if there is a typo in either, you may miss out on an interview opportunity entirely. Place your contact information prominently at the top of your resume where it is immediately visible.\n"
"\n"
"Include your full name in a slightly larger font size than the rest of your resume to make it stand out. Below your name, list your phone number with a professional voicemail greeting, your email address, and your general location. You do not need to include your full street address; city and state (or city and country for international applications) are sufficient. Many job seekers today also omit their location entirely, particularly if they are open to remote work.\n"
"\n"
"Your email address should be professional and straightforward. Ideally, it should be some variation of your name, such as firstname.lastname@email.com. If your name is common and the obvious variations are taken, use a professional alternative like firstnameMlastname or firstnamelastname.career. Avoid nicknames, numbers that suggest your birth year, or anything that could be perceived as unprofessional.\n"
"\n"
"Consider adding links to your LinkedIn profile, personal website, or online portfolio if they are relevant and up-to-date. A strong LinkedIn presence can reinforce your resume and provide additional context that does not fit in a one-to-two-page document. However, only include these links if the content they lead to is polished and professional. An incomplete LinkedIn profile or an outdated portfolio will work against you rather than for you.\n"
"\n"
"Do not include personal details such as your age, date of birth, marital status, nationality, or a photograph unless these are specifically required by the job posting or are standard practice in the country where you are applying. In the United States, including such information can expose both you and the employer to potential discrimination liability and is considered inappropriate."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"Your cover letter and resume are two distinct documents with different purposes, yet many candidates use the cover letter simply to restate their resume in paragraph form. This is a wasted opportunity that adds no value to your application. If the hiring manager reads your cover letter and learns nothing new, they have no additional reason to be interested in you.\n"
"\n"
"A resume is a factual summary of your qualifications -- job titles, dates, bullet-pointed achievements, and skills. A cover letter, by contrast, is a narrative document that provides context, motivation, and personality. It should answer questions your resume cannot: Why are you interested in this specific role? What drove you to make particular career decisions? How do your diverse experiences come together to make you uniquely qualified?\n"
"\n"
"Instead of repeating that you \"managed a team of 12 engineers,\" your cover letter should explain what you learned about leadership from that experience and how it prepared you for the challenges of the role you are applying for. Instead of listing your technical skills again, describe a specific project where you applied those skills to solve a meaningful problem and what the results meant for the business.\n"
"\n"
"Think of your resume as the \"what\" and your cover letter as the \"why\" and \"how.\" Together, they should paint a complete picture of you as a candidate. The hiring manager should finish reading both documents feeling like they understand not just your qualifications, but your motivations, your thought process, and your potential for growth."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"Your cover letter header establishes your professional identity and makes it easy for the hiring manager to contact you. A well-designed header creates visual consistency with your resume and reinforces your personal brand. Include your full name, phone number, email address, and optionally your LinkedIn profile URL or professional portfolio link.\n"
"\n"
"Place your contact information at the top of the page. You have two primary options for layout: a traditional block format where your information is left-aligned above the date and recipient's details, or a modern centered header that matches your resume design. If you are using a resume builder like IMTA Resume that generates matching header designs, this consistency creates a polished, cohesive application package.\n"
"\n"
"Below your contact information, include the date followed by the recipient's details: their name, title, company name, and company address. If you are submitting through an online portal where this information would be redundant, you may omit the recipient's mailing address and simply use their name and title. Always try to address your letter to a specific person rather than using a generic greeting.\n"
"\n"
"For email submissions, the header format can be slightly simplified since your email itself provides contact details. However, if attaching the cover letter as a PDF (which is recommended), include the full header to ensure your contact information is always visible regardless of how the file is shared or printed within the organization.\n"
"\n"
"Keep the header clean and uncluttered. Avoid decorative elements, colored backgrounds, or excessive design flourishes that might not render properly across different devices and software. Simple formatting with clear typography ensures your header looks professional on any screen."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid "Your cover letter opening paragraph should be two to three sentences, or roughly 40 to 60 words. This is enough space to identify the role, present a compelling hook, and establish your strongest qualification. Longer openings risk losing the reader's attention before you reach your key points. Think of the opening as a strategic first impression, not a comprehensive introduction."
msgstr ""

#: src/routes/dashboard/tools/-components/ai-writer-panels-b.tsx
msgid "Your cover letter will appear here"
msgstr "Votre lettre de motivation apparaîtra ici"

#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"Your cover letter's closing paragraph determines the final impression you leave with the hiring manager and directly influences whether they take the next step with your application. Psychology research on the \"recency effect\" shows that people disproportionately remember the last thing they read, making your conclusion one of the most strategically important sections of your entire letter.\n"
"\n"
"Despite this, many candidates treat the closing as an afterthought, defaulting to a tepid \"Thank you for your consideration\" that does nothing to differentiate them from the competition. A strong closing paragraph, by contrast, reinforces your value proposition, demonstrates confidence, and creates a clear path forward for the next stage of the hiring process.\n"
"\n"
"Think of your closing as the final argument in a persuasion case. A trial lawyer does not end their closing statement with \"Well, I hope you found that convincing.\" They end with a powerful, memorable summation that makes the desired verdict feel inevitable. Your cover letter closing should do the same -- it should make inviting you for an interview feel like the obvious next step.\n"
"\n"
"The ideal closing paragraph is three to four sentences long and accomplishes three specific objectives: it briefly reinforces why you are an excellent fit, it expresses genuine enthusiasm for the specific opportunity, and it includes a proactive call to action that signals your confidence and initiative. Mastering this formula will significantly increase your callback rate."
msgstr ""

