#: src/data/wiki/categories/salary-negotiation.ts
msgid ""
"Your first negotiation should consider not just the starting number but the growth trajectory. Ask about the company's raise cycle, typical increase percentages, promotion timelines, and bonus structures. A company that offers a slightly lower starting salary but promotes aggressively and gives generous annual increases may be a better long-term financial decision than a company with a higher starting salary and minimal growth.\n"
"\n"
"Negotiate for an early performance review if possible. Many companies conduct annual reviews, meaning a new hire who starts in January will not be reviewed for a raise until the following January. Negotiating a six-month review with the potential for a salary adjustment gives you an earlier opportunity to demonstrate your value and capture an increase.\n"
"\n"
"If the company has a structured new graduate program with defined salary bands and progression schedules, ask for the details of how advancement works. Understanding the path from Level 1 to Level 2, including the typical timeline, required competencies, and salary band for each level, helps you plan your career development strategically.\n"
"\n"
"Start building your negotiation portfolio from day one. Document your accomplishments, quantify your contributions, and collect positive feedback from colleagues and managers. When your first review comes around, you will have a well-organized case for an above-average increase rather than relying on your manager to remember your contributions from months ago.\n"
"\n"
"Finally, remember that your first job is rarely your last. If you cannot negotiate the compensation you want at this stage, focus on building skills, experience, and relationships that maximize your value for the next negotiation. Many professionals see their largest salary jumps when changing jobs early in their career, so invest in making yourself as marketable as possible during your first two to three years."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/salary-negotiation.ts
msgid ""
"Your first salary is not just your starting paycheck. It is the foundation upon which your entire career earnings trajectory is built. Future raises, bonuses, and even offers from other companies are often calculated as percentages of your current compensation. A difference of just five thousand dollars in your first salary can compound into hundreds of thousands of dollars over a 30-year career.\n"
"\n"
"Many new graduates feel they have no leverage to negotiate because they lack experience. This is a misconception. Companies invest significant resources in campus recruiting, interviewing, and selecting candidates, and they want their chosen candidates to accept. The fact that you received an offer means the company has already decided you are worth hiring, which gives you more leverage than you might think.\n"
"\n"
"The discomfort with negotiation is natural and universal. Studies show that new graduates are the least likely demographic to negotiate their first offer, with only about 20 percent attempting any negotiation at all. This means that 80 percent of new professionals are leaving money on the table before their careers even begin. Simply being willing to negotiate puts you ahead of the vast majority of your peers.\n"
"\n"
"Your first negotiation also sets a psychological precedent for your entire career. If you negotiate successfully early on, you build confidence and skills that compound just like the financial returns. Every subsequent negotiation becomes easier because you have proven to yourself that asking for what you are worth produces positive results."
msgstr ""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"Your freelance career has given you a broader professional network than most traditional employees have. Leveraging this network strategically is one of the most effective ways to find and secure a full-time position.\n"
"\n"
"Your existing clients are your most valuable networking resource. If you have clients whose organizations you admire, let them know you are interested in full-time opportunities. Many freelancers transition to full-time roles with former clients, as these employers already know the quality of your work and your ability to integrate with their team. Even if your current clients do not have openings, they may refer you to colleagues at other organizations.\n"
"\n"
"Reconnect with colleagues you have met through project work, coworking spaces, industry events, and professional communities. Let your network know that you are actively seeking a full-time position and what type of role you are looking for. Be specific about your goals so that people can make targeted introductions. A message like \"I am looking for a senior product design role at a mid-size SaaS company in the fintech space\" is far more actionable than \"I am looking for a full-time job.\"\n"
"\n"
"Update your LinkedIn profile to reflect your transition goals. Your headline should signal your interest in full-time opportunities while highlighting your expertise. Something like \"Senior UX Designer | 8 Years of Design Leadership Across 50+ Projects | Open to Full-Time Opportunities\" tells recruiters exactly what you offer and what you are looking for.\n"
"\n"
"Attend industry events and meetups regularly. As a freelancer, you may have focused on client acquisition at these events. Shift your mindset to networking for employment. Build relationships with hiring managers, team leads, and recruiters in your target industry. The personal connections you make can bypass the applicant tracking system and put your resume directly in front of decision-makers."
msgstr ""

