#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"Your professional summary is arguably the most important section of a career change resume. It sits at the top of the document and sets the tone for everything that follows. A well-written summary can frame your transition as a natural evolution rather than a radical departure.\n"
"\n"
"The ideal career change summary follows a three-part structure. First, identify yourself with a title or descriptor relevant to your target field, not your current one. Second, highlight two to three transferable skills or achievements that directly support your candidacy. Third, state your career objective or the value you aim to bring to the new role.\n"
"\n"
"Avoid generic statements like \"seeking new challenges\" or \"looking to leverage my skills.\" These phrases add no value and waste precious real estate at the top of your resume. Instead, be specific about what you offer: \"Operations manager with 12 years of experience streamlining workflows and reducing costs, bringing process optimization expertise to the UX design field through a human-centered approach to system efficiency.\"\n"
"\n"
"Your summary should also address the elephant in the room: why you are changing careers. You do not need to write a paragraph about it, but a brief acknowledgment shows self-awareness and intentionality. Phrases like \"transitioning from\" or \"pivoting into\" signal that you are making a deliberate choice rather than fleeing a bad situation.\n"
"\n"
"Test your summary by showing it to someone in your target industry. Ask them if it makes you sound like a viable candidate. If they immediately ask \"but what industry were you in before?\", your summary is doing its job of leading with relevance rather than history."
msgstr ""

